<P>The following is the transcript of the second part of Robert Kardashian's deposition, taken on May 14, 1996.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA
FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES

SHARON RUFO, Plaintiff,

vs.

ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al., Defendants

DEPOSITION OF ROBERT G. KARDASHIAN Los Angeles, California May 14,
1996 DAVID S. COLEMAN CSR #4613 JOB NO 96-1431

SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS
ANGELES

SHARON RUFO, Plaintiff,

vs.

ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al., Defendants

FREDRIC GOLDMAN, etc., et al., Plaintiffs,

vs.

ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al., Defendants

LOUIS H BROWN, etc., Plaintiffs,

vs.

ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, Defendant

VOLUME II

Continued videotaped deposition of ROBERT G. KARDASHIAN, taken on
behalf of the Plaintiffs, at 11377 West Olympic Boulevard, 10th Floor,
Los Angeles, California, commencing at 9:40 a.m., on Tuesday, May 14,
1996 before David S. Coleman, CSR #4613, pursuant to Subpoena.

APPEARANCES: FOR THE PLAINTIFFS FREDRIC GOLDMAN, ET AL: MITCHELL,
SILBERBERG & KNUPP BY: DANIEL M. PETROCELLI, ESQ. ARTHUR GROMAN, ESQ.
11377 West Olympic Boulevard Sixth Floor Los Angeles, California
90064-1683

FOR THE PLAINTIFF ESTATE OF BROWN: JOHN QUINLAN KELLY, ESQ. 330
Madison Avenue New York, New York 10017-5090 (212) 682-1700 (Of record
but not present) -and- NATASHA ROIT, ESQ. 116 North Robertston
Boulevard Suite 705 Los Angeles, California 90048 (Of record but not
present)

FOR THE PLAINTIFF SHARON RUFO: HORNBERGER & CRISWELL BY: MICHAEL A.
BREWER, ESQ. 444 South Flower Street Thirty-First Floor Los Angeles,
California 90071

FOR THE DEFENDANT ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON: BAKER, SILBERBERG & KEENER
BY: PHILIP BAKER, ESQ. 2850 Ocean Park Boulevard Suite 300 Santa
Monica, California 90405-2936 -and- BAILEY, FISHMAN & LEONARD BY:
DANIEL LEONARD, ESQ. 66 Long Wharf Boston, Massachusetts 02110 (617)
723-1980 -and- ROBERT D. BLASIER, ESQ. 6355 Riverside Boulevard Suite
2-F Sacramento, California 95831 (916) 427-1600 (Of record but not
present)

FOR THE WITNESS: MICHAELSON & LEVINE BY: JANET I. LEVINE, ESQ. 1901
Avenue of the Stars Suite 1708 Los Angeles, California 90067

ALSO PRESENT: FREDRIC GOLDMAN


EXHIBITS: 201 Deposition Subpoena and Production Documents and Things
of Robert Kardashian dated February 2, 1995, 5 pages 202 Transcript of
"Larry King Live" show dated October 6, 1995, 24 pages 203 Copy of
calendar, incoming calls and outgoing call, 17 pages 204 Handwritten
document containing the name of a woman allegedly being seen by O.J.
Simpson while he was married to Nicole 205 Handwritten document
containing the names of persons attending the 50th birthday party of
Mr. Kardashian 206 Police report of Robert Kardashian dated 6-17-94

THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Good morning. Here begins videotape No. 1 in the
deposition of Robert Kardashian Volume II in the consolidated cases of
Fredric Goldman, Sharon Rufo and Louis Brown vs. Orenthal James
Simpson in the Superior Court, State of California, County of Los
Angeles, the lead case number of which is SC 031947.

Today's date is Tuesday, May 14, 1996. The time is approximately 9:41.
This deposition is being taken at 11377 West Olympic Boulevard in Los
Angles, California and was made at the request of plaintiff of the Law
Offices of Mitchell, Silberberg & Knupp.

The videographer is Rod Rigole, employed by Coleman, Haas, Martin and
Schwab of Los Angeles, California.

Would counsel please identify yourselves and state whom you represent.

Mr. Petrocelli: Daniel Petrocelli for Plaintiff Fredric Goldman.

Mr. Groman: Arthur Groman for Plaintiff Fredric Goldman.

Mr. Brewer: Michael Brewer for Plaintiff Sharon Rufo.

Mr. Baker: Phil Baker for O.J. Simpson.

Ms. Levine: Janet Levine on behalf of the witness, Robert Kardashian.

Robert G. Kardashian, having been previously sworn, was examined and
testified further as follows.

EXAMINATION (Resumed)

By Mr. Petrocelli:

Q: Good morning, Mr. Kardashian. You are still under oath from the
first session of your deposition. You understand that?

A: Yes, I do.

Q: Between that session and today's have you done anything to prepare
for today's session.

A: No, I have not.

Q: Have you read anything?

A: Yes. I read my transcript of the deposition.

Q: The first session, given on May 3?

A: Yes sir.

Q: Did you note anything that was inaccurate or incorrect?

A: There are a few minor inconsistencies, but I couldn't tell you what
they are right now. I'd have to go through it.

Q: Did you make any notes?

A: No, I did not.

Q: Okay. Have you had any conversations with anyone regarding your
deposition other than Miss Levine?

A: No, I have not.

Q: Have you spoken to Mr. Simpson since the last session of your
deposition.

A: Yes, I did.

Q: On how many occasions?

A: I just believe one. He called last night.

Q: From London?

A: Yes sir.

Q: What was the discussion?

Mr. Baker: I'd object to that question on the grounds it calls for
attorney-client communications.

By Mr. Petrocelli:

Q: Can you answer that?

A: That I could answer. I was asleep and he woke me up, and he was
with a friend of ours from England and just said -- he wanted to say
hello, this friend , and he said, "Why are you asleep?"

And I said, "Well, it's" whatever time it was. I said, "whatever time
it was." I said, "I have my deposition tomorrow."

And he said, "Oh, well, then I better not talk to you."

And I said, "Yeah, you better not," and I hung up.

Q: What time was it L.A. time?

A: I'm not sure. I think it was 10:30 or about 11:00.

Q: Is that the only time --

A: Yes.

Q: -- you've spoken to Mr. Simpson since the first session of your
deposition?

A: Yes, sir.

Q: Okay. What is your current occupation? What is it that you do right
now?

A: I'm president of a company called Movie Tunes.

Q: And you've been -- you own that company?

A: Yes, sir.

Q: You own all the stock?

A: Yes, sir.

Q: And you've been running Movie Tunes since how long?

A: I believe 1992.

Q: How many employees do you have?

A: Well, it varies. I've got right now only-only two employees right
now.

Q: During the criminal trial, preliminary trial, the
actual-preliminary hearing, the trial itself, during all the time that
you were involved with Mr. Simpson's criminal matters, were you
tending, to your business?

MS. LEVINE: Involved in the sense that he was a lawyer? What do you
mean, ''involved"? It's a vague term.

BY MR. PETROCELL:

Q: Whatever you were doing, you were sitting at counsel's table,
acting, I suppose, as a lawyer and giving assistance to Mr. Simpson.

During all that period of time, who was running your business?

A: I was attempting to.

Q: Okay. Do you have an assistant?

A: Yes.

Q: And what is that person's name?

A: Michael Ameen was the assistant at the time.

Q: How do you spell his last name?

A: A-m-e-e-n.

Q: Okay. Is he still with you?

A: No, he is not.

Q: Okay. And when did he leave?

A: I would estimate maybe a year ago, six, eight months ago, something
like that.

Q: Was Mr. Ameen with you as of June l2, 1994?

A: Yes, sir.

Q: Okay. And who-what other employees, were with you as of that time?

A: Nicole Pulvers.

Q: What was her position with your company?

A: She was an attorney and an administrative assistant. Barbara
Stockton was my assistant, and Michael Ameen. Those were the
individuals I had at that time.

Q: Michael was your -- what was his position?

A: Michael was my head of sales and marketing, basically.

Q: And where was your office as of that time?

A: Offices were in my home.

Q: They have been in your home since 1992?

A: Yes.

Q: To the present.

A: Yes.

Q: Okay. How is Movie Tunes spelled? Is Tunes T-o-o-n-s or T-u-n-s-

A: T-u-n-e-s-

Q: -e-s.

A: -two words.

Q: Has the business of Movie Tunes declined as a result of your
participation in the Simpson case?

MS. LEVINE: Objection. Calls for speculation, and I don't know how far
down a field you are going to go with this into his financial affairs
at the present time. I don't think that that's anything that's any of
your business.

If you want to ask him questions -- preliminary questions like you've
been asking, that's fine, but I don't want you to go deep a field.
It's not at issue in this case, and he has some privacy rights despite
the fact that he's a witness before you.

MR. PETROCELLI: Okay hear what you're saying.

Q: Can you answer the question?

A: Repeat that again, please.

MR. PETROCELLI: You want to repeat it again, David?

(Pending question read as follows: "Q. Has the business of Movie Tunes
declined as a result of your participation in the Simpson case?")

THE WITNESS: Yes.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Substantially?

A: Yes.

Q: Okay. Can you give me just a ballpark percentage as to how far your
business is off?

MS. LEVINE: Percentage without getting into numbers?

MR. BAKER: I am just going to object on relevancy grounds.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: I am not really interested in the numbers. I just want to know the
percentage of what do you think your business is off as a result of
your participation in Mr. Simpson's case.

A: Perhaps 40 to 50 percent.

Q: And was Movie Tunes your sole source of income prior to June 12,
1994?

Q: Your principal source of income?

A: Yes.

Q: Okay. Your only active source of income. Right?

MS. LEVINE: Objection, vague.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: In other words, you might have passive investments, but this is the
only business you were running. Is that true?

A: No.

Q: What other business were you running at the time as of June
12,1994?

A: A company called Hit Tunes.

Q: Hit Tunes? And you still-did you own Hit Tunes?

A: Yes.

Q: Hundred percent?

A: Yes.

Q: And you still own it?

A: Yes.

Q: And is it still operating?

A: Yes.

Q: Operates also out of your house?

A: Yes.

Q: Do the same people work for Hit Tunes who work for Movie Tunes?

A: Basically, yes.

Q: Do you have any different personnel?

A: Sometimes I do. Hit Tunes is a little bit different than Movie
Tunes.

Q: Explain the two companies very briefly.

A: Well, briefly, Hit Tunes was set up to sell CDs via CD vending
machines in movie theater lobbies.

Q: Hit Tunes?

A: Yes. And as a result, I had different people who would stock and
rack those machines and watch over that. Whereas Movie Tunes provides
actual music to the movie theaters itself.

Q: Was Movie Tunes a bigger company providing a larger source of
income to you than Hit Tunes?

A: Most definitely

Q: Okay. And has the business of Hit Tunes suffered as a result of
your participation in the Simpson case?

MS. LEVINE: Same objections.

MR. BAKER: Irrelevant and vague.

THE WITNESS: It's suffered. I don't know if it's a result of the case,
but it has suffered because of my time.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Is it off 40, 50 percent?

A: It's more difficult to- it's more than that, so it's more difficult
to characterize.

Q: Is the reason that your businesses- by "businesses," I mean Movie
Tunes and Hit Tunes- have suffered as a result of your participation
in the Simpson case attributable simply to your absence from the
business?

A: Yes.

MS. LEVINE: Object-

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Okay. Has your business suffered in any way as a result of any
public stigma or rejection by the public associated with you and your
business?

MS. LEVINE: Objection. Calls for speculation. There is no way he could
know that.

MR. BAKER: And it's irrelevant.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: You may answer.

MS. LEVINE: If you can.

THE WITNESS: I really don't know. You know, I don't-no one's told me,
"We're not going to do business with you because of this," so I really
don't know for sure.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: So based on your knowledge and experience in your business, you
don't believe that that's happening.

MS. LEVINE.: Objection. Misstates the testimony and is argumentative.
He said he didn't know.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Is that accurate?

MR. BAKER: And it's irrelevant.

THE WITNESS: No, I don't think-I don't think your statement is
accurate. I don't know.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: You do not know--

A: No.

Q:-one way or the other?

A: No, I don't.

Q: Okay. Have you suffered any diminution in your standing or stature
in the social community as a result of your participation on the
Simpson defense team?

MR. BAKER: Speculative-

MS. LEVINE: Objection. Irrelevant, calls for speculation. and it
invades his privacy right.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: You can answer.

MS. LEVINE: This is how he's being treated now by people out in the
world? What does that have to do with

MR. PETROCELLI: It's highly relevant to his motive and his bias and
his credibility in giving testimony as a material witness in this
case.

MS. LEVINE: I can't see how it's relevant at all to anything.

MR. PETROCELLI: I don't know what to tell you. I am just telling you
what the argument is.

MS. LEVINE: You know, if you want to sit here all day and ask him
questions like that, that's fine, and he can answer this one, but I am
not going to let us sit here all day and answer silly questions like
this.

THE WITNESS: I'm sorry. Repeat it.

MR. PETROCELLI: Yeah, you can repeat the question, please.

(Pending question read as follows:

"Q. Okay. Have you suffered any diminution in your standing or stature
in the social community as a result of your participation on the
Simpson defense team?")

THE WITNESS: Yes.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Okay. In what respect?

MR. BAKER: Same objection: Irrelevant.

MS. LEVINE: Same objections.

THE WITNESS: Yeah, I don't - I mean, I can't quantify it.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: No. Describe to me what has happened as a result.

A: Just negative comments people make to me.

Q: Do you have more trouble getting reservations in your favorite
restaurants, things like that?

A: No. No, that's not a problem, because I've always been -- I've been
born and raised here, so I've always frequented the same
establishments I'm frequenting today, so -- and I've known these
people for years, so it isn't-that isn't a problem. It's just
sometimes how I'm treated by the man on the street that I don't know.

Q: Just members of the general public-

A: Correct.

Q:-making negative comments?

A: Correct.

Q: Is that what you meant?

A: Yes.

Q: Okay. Do you have any agreement to write a book?

MS. LEVINE: Objection. I am going to object to that as being
irrelevant and also invading his privacy rights. I think in the last
deposition the same question was asked, and I believe the same
objection was made. I don't have a copy of it.

MR. PETROCELLI: Well, this question wasn't asked, but the topic was
generally raised.

MS. LEVINE: Can I see - I don't have a copy. Can I-do you have an
unmarked copy? I don't want to look at your markings.

MR. PETROCELLI: Well-

MR. BAKER: I do. I don't have a word index, but-

MR. PETROCELLI: I don't want to have to spend a lot of time going back
over whatever another lawyer  in this case asked.

MS. LEVINE: I don't either. I just don't think that any financial
arrangements he may or may not have at this time are relevant. I am
not going to let him answer it. I think it goes into his privacy
rights that he still has.

MR. PETROCELLI: Well, his privacy rights, if he has any in this kind
of matter, give way to the need to disclose information that is
relevant to his motivation, bias and credibility as a material
witness.

MR. BAKER: I don't

MS. LEVINE: Well, I guess that that's an arguable point that we may
have to argue some day, but we are not going to decide it right here,
I don't think.

Do you know what page it's on?

MR. PETROCELLI: It's on page 69, et seq.

MS. LEVINE: I instructed him not to answer.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Do you have a current deal with anyone to write a book?

MS. LEVINE: Same objection and same instruction.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Are you currently involved in writing a book?

MS LEVINE: Same objection and same instruction.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Have you provided any information to anyone else regarding a book
written by another person?

MS. LEVINE: Same objection and same instruction.

MR. PETROCELLI: What is the basis for that? That doesn't go to his
writing, a book. If he tells another person information that in any
way relates to this case, I am entitled to know that information.

MS LEVINE: If you want to go into things that he may have told someone
at some point, go into what he knows. Anything that he is doing right
now has nothing to do with his percipient witness knowledge, think you
have no business asking about. don't think the fact that you issue a
subpoena to him lays bare his entire personal life.

MR. PETROCELLI: I have the right to inquire what he is telling other
persons about this case, whether it's in the context of providing
information for a book or in some other context.

MS. LEVINE: Well-

MR. PETROCELLI: It could, number one, elicit direct admissions. Number
two, it could lead to other relevant and discoverable information.

MS. LEVINE: Well, certainly it couldn't be an admission since he is
not a party.

MR. PETROCELLI: Might be an authorized admission of O.J. Simpson if he
is his representative.

MS. LEVINE: And in any event, I am going to instruct him not to answer
that.

MR. PETROCELLI: Excuse me. What if he told another person, "O.J.
Simpson told me X, Y and Z"?

MS. LEVINE: I think if he said that, he'd have a privilege issue, but
--

MR. PETROCELLI: Well, I have a right to inquire whether he said those
things. You can't just cut me off at the pass. I mean, that's what
this deposition is all about. I am entitled to go beyond things he
actually witnessed at the time into his discussions since the time
that relate to this case.

MS. LEVINE: You are asking him about anything he may have had to do
with writing a book, and I am instructing him not to answer.

MR. PETROCELLI: Well, we talked about his book, and you've instructed
him, and we will go to court on that. Now I am asking whether he has
ever provided any information to anyone else, not in connection with a
book for which he is being paid or that he is writing, but that
someone else may be writing. There is no invasion of his privacy
there.

MS. LEVINE: Well, I am going to object. Same objection.

MR. PETROCELLI: On what ground?

MS. LEVINE: Privacy grounds.

MR. PETROCELLI: Okay

MR. BAKER: And could you invade the attorney-client privilege.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Okay. Have you had any discussions with Larry Schiller about the
preparation of a book by Mr. Schiller or by anyone else?

MR. BAKER: I think this was-

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

MS. LEVINE: Same objection and same instruction.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: When was the last time you spoke to Mr. Schiller?

MS. LEVINE: That may have been asked and answered.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: You spoke to him the day before May 3, when asked last time. Now I
am asking as of today.

MS. LEVINE: Whether he has spoken with him between May 3 and today?

MR. PETROCELLI: I guess that would logically follow.

MS. LEVINE: Well, I may not be as smart as you to figure that out, so
I'm trying to make sure.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: You may answer.

A: Yes.

Q: Okay.

A: I'm sorry. Did I speak to him?

Q: Yes. Since-the last time you testified that you spoke to Mr.
Schiller on May 2.

MR. BAKER: What page is that?

MR. PETROCELLI: It's on page 70, line 18.

Q: Did you speak to Mr. Schiller on May 3, the day of your deposition?

A: No, I don't believe so.

Q: And have you spoken to him since May 3?

A: Yes.

Q: Up to today, which is May 14th?

A: Yes.

Q: And what did-how many times have you spoken to one another?

A: Maybe two or three.

Q: Okay. And have you met with him in person?

A: No, I haven't.

Q: And these have all been telephone conversations?

A: Yes, sir.

Q: Okay. And what's the substance of those conversations?

A: Well, I can recall I spoke with him this morning. He called me and
said, "Did you see the newspaper? It said there is a lien, or the IRS
has a lien. O.J., according to the paper, didn't pay his taxes."

I said, "No, I haven't seen the newspaper," and that was the
conversation.

Q: And did you have any other conversations with him-

A: No. That was today.

Q: -between May 3-

A: Oh, yeah, I did-

Q: -and today?

