MS. LEVINE: It's - as you may or may not know-I don't know what your
experience in the criminal field is-the Grand Jury proceeding is
different than most other proceedings because it's not adversary, in
the sense that nobody can appear on behalf of the person that's
potentially accused of the crime. So any objections that are made have
to be made in advance very broadly, and generally the feeling is that
any- thing goes within the Grand Jury, and then if there is a problem
later, it's sorted out later.

What happened in this case was basically the judge said it's not a
Simpson Grand Jury; it's a Cowlings Grand Jury, and nothing related to
Simpson should be asked. But, of course, Mr. Simpson's lawyers could
not be present and I couldn't be present just because of the nature of
the Grand Jury.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: But the court issued an order directing you to testify in some
limited capacity prior to your testifying. Right?

A: That's correct.

