Q: Do you remember actually taking the bag out of Taft's car?

A: No. I believe she was already standing on the sidewalk with the bag
in her hand.

Q: Okay.  And when you said, "Let me take that from you," where did
you want to take it to?

A: I just meant, Let me hold it for you.

Q: Did you know whose bag it was?

A: I just assumed it was Mr. Simpson's-I had no idea, but I assumed it
was Mr. Simpson's bag.

Q: You didn't know whether it was Cathy Randa's bag.

A: That's correct. I just held it just to be a gentleman.

Q: So when you asked the police if you could bring the bag to Mr.
Simpson, that was based on an assumption that it was his bag. Right?

A: No. I believe a few minutes later she told me that this is O.J.'s
bag, and then I went up to the police. I didn't go to the police
immediately after taking the bag from Cathy. We stood over on the side
for a few minutes.

Q: And your purpose in going to the policeman -- I think you described
him as an African-American?

A: Yes.

Q: 6 foot 6?

A: Around there.

Q: Your purpose in going to this --  you know his name, by the way?

A: No, I do not.

Q: Your purpose in going to him was to see if you could go in the
house with the bag and bring it to the house?

MR. BAKER: Asked and answered.

THE WITNESS: No. My purpose was to give him the bag. I had attempted
to get in before that time, and he didn't let me in.

BY MR. PETROCELLI:

Q: Do you recall telling him, "This is O.J. Simpson's luggage, and you
must get it to him"?

A: No. I recall telling him, "I have  O.J. Simpson's"-"I have Mr.
Simpson's luggage, and you should take it in."

And he said, "No, you can't come in."

Q: Did you ask him to take it?

A: Yes.

Q: And he said no.

A: He said no.

Q: Did you ask for any instructions as to what to do with the bag?

A: No.

Q: And did you approach any other policeman or detective about what to
do with this bag?

A: No, I did not.

Q: Okay. And when you saw Mr. Simpson in handcuffs, did you try to get
