Los Angeles, California 90071 (Of record but

not present)



FOR THE DEFENDANT ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON: 

BAKER, SILBERBERG & KEENER

2850 Ocean Park Boulevard Suite 300 

Santa Monica California 90405-2938

(Of record but not present) 



-and- 



BAILEY, FISHMAN & LEONARD 

BY: DANIEL LEONARD, ESQ. 

66 Long Wharf Boston, Massachusetts 02110 (617) 723-1980



-and- 



ROBERT D. BLASIER, ESQ. 

6355 Riverside Boulevard Suite 2-F

Sacramento, California 95831 (916) 427-1600 (Of record but not

present)



FOR THE WITNESS: 

DAVIS WRIGHT TREMAINE 

BY: KELLI L. SAGER, ESQ. 1000

Wilshire Boulevard Suite 600 Los Angeles, California 90017



WITNESS:



LAWRENCE J. SCHILLER Examination by Mr. Gelblum



EXHIBITS:



234 Notice of Depositions of Lawrence Schiller Custodian of Records of

Polaris Communications, Inc. dated February 27, 1996, 10 pages



235 Objections of Non-parties Polaris Communications, Inc. and

Lawrence Schiller to Subpoenas Duces Tecum dated June 4, 1996, 22

pages



236 Document entitled "Forward," 8 pages



LAWRENCE J. SCHILLER,  having been first duly sworn, was examined and

testified as follows:



EXAMINATION BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: State your full name for the record, please.



A: Lawrence Schiller.



Q:  I heard you say earlier you do have a middle initial?



A: Yes, but I don't use it. It's J.



Q:  But it's on your birth certificate?



A: No, it's not.



MR. LEONARD:  Don't even go down that road.



MR. GELBLUM:  I have decided not to.



MS. SAGER:  Thank you.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q:  Have you had your deposition taken before, Mr. Schiller?



A: I have.



Q: And have you had an opportunity to discuss with your counsel the

procedures that we will be going through?



A: I have.



Q: Do you  have any questions before we begin?



A: No.



Q: Have you taken any medication this morning or in the last 24 hours

that would affect your ability to listen, understand and answer my

questions?



A: I have not taken any medication.



Q: Have you taken anything that would(ingested anything in the last 24

hours that would affect your ability to listen to, understand and

answer my questions?



A: I have not digested anything.



Q: Have you inhaled anything?



A: I have not inhaled anything.



Q: All right. Do you anticipate any problem with understanding or

answering my questions?



A: Yes.



Q: You do.



A: Yes.



Q: What problem is that?



A: I have dyslexia, and many times I accidentally say different time

periods or dates or  names. I might be thinking of one name, and

accidentally it comes out another. And I have  difficulty reading

sometimes. I look at a word and the(I guess my brain takes the

letters, and I think for a second it's a different word. But I was ( I

havedyslexia.



Q: I always thought dyslexia only had to do with the written word.

It's also the spoken word?



A: Yes, there is a form of it. If I'm very slow and careful, I'm okay,

but if I go a little too fast, my mind thinks slightly different, so I

will try to keep myself slow.



Q: I prefer, obviously, that you go more slowly and be more accurate.



A: Yeah.



Q: When this happens, when you mix up dates or people's names(



A: Mostly people's names.



Q: (when do you realize that you've done that?



A: Sometimes I don't. People have to point it out to me.



MR. LEONARD: Peter, you might want to(I am sure he knows, but you

might want to remind him of the  opportunity to look at the deposition

afterwards.



MR. GELBLUM: Oh, sure, but he has trouble reading sometimes, so(



THE WITNESS: Right, but(





BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Your counsel, I am sure, will read it to you and point out any

errors she thinks exist.



A: Right. I just wanted to make you aware of it.



Q: I appreciate it. That's why I asked the question.



A: Sure.



Q: But from now on I will ask about conditions and not just things

people have ingested, which I have never done before.



MR. LEONARD: There you go.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Are you represented by counsel today?



A: I am.



Q: Is it Miss Sager?



A: It is.



Q: Did you do anything to prepare for today's deposition?



A: I just had a conversation with my attorney before I came here.



Q: That's it?



A: (Nods head.)



THE REPORTER: You're nodding your head.



THE WITNESS: Yes.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: You need to answer audibly. That's my fault. David needs you to

answer with words that he can take down rather than gestures or(



A: Right.



Q:( non-verbal responses.  All right?



MR. LEONARD: You don't have to worry, because he will definitely tell

you.



MS. SAGER: The other thing that I noticed just if I can inject for a

minute, you have to make sure that Mr. Gelblum is done asking a

question before you start to answer because it's really hard for the

court reporter to take down two people, because even one word, like

saying "right" when someone else is talking, he is going to have

trouble with.



MR. LEONARD: Plus one more thing: that also gives me an opportunity to

object if I need to, and if I object, unless your attorney instructs

you not to answer, you must and should answer the question.



THE WITNESS: Thank you.



MR. GELBLUM: Thank you.



MR. LEONARD: Well, I'm here for you.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did you review any documents in  preparation for the deposition?



A: No.



Q: Have you spoken with Mr. Leonard before this moment?



A: Yes.



Q: How many times?



A: About five months ago I met him, and then I spoke to him now.



Q: Just before the deposition started?



A: 10 minutes ago.



Q: All right. Did you discuss anything about what was going to be

discussed in the deposition?



A: No.



Q: Did you discuss anything about this case?



A:  About the case?



Q: Yes.



A: No.



Q: When you met five months ago, where was that?



A: North Carolina.



MR. LEONARD: Burlington.



THE WlTNESS: Burlington.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: What were the circumstances?



A: I was meeting with Mr. Bailey.



Q: About this case?



A: No.



Q: Did you discuss this case at all with Mr. Bailey or Mr. Leonard at

that time?



A: No.



MR. LEONARD: We were trying a murder case.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: So the only times you spoke with Mr. Leonard were that one occasion

in Burlington and this morning?



A: I just said hello to him. We walked in and out of the room and we

said hi, and this morning.



Q: Those were the only two times?



A: To the best of my memory.



Q: Have you ever discussed the Simpson case with Mr. Bailey?



MS. SAGER: I am going to object at this point to any questions

directed to conversations that Mr. Schiller may or may not have had

with any particular individual that were done in the course of him

gathering information for preparation of any material for

dissemination to the public, including books, magazines, videotapes

films, on the basis that it interferes with his rights under the First

Amentiment, the California Reporter's Shield, under Article I, Section

2(b) of the California Constitution Evidence Code Section 1070 and the

common law, and any answers Mr. Schiller gives to any questions

involving discussions he may or may not have had with any particular

individual will be limited to any conversations he had that were

outside the context of any information he was gathering for

preparation of any of the materials I've described.



MR. GELBLUM: Could you read that back, please.



MS. SAGER: And for purposes of brevity, if you would prefer in the

future I will simply say, "We are objecting on the grounds of the

reporter's privilege," and ask you to rephrase the question, rather

than giving the whole litany.



MR. GELBLUM: That would be preferable, but I do want to hear the exact

parameters.



MS. SAGER: Sure.



MS. SAGER: And I guess I would add I am not intending to limit by

specifying those materials if it was gathered for some other type of

material for disseminadon to the public: Newspapers, television shows,

et cetera.



MR. GELBLUM: As you know, Miss Sager, we discussed this issue before

the deposition, and we have disagreements about the extent of the

application of the reporter's privilege to Mr. Schiller's

conversations and his work, which we almost certainly will take up

with the court after this, but I wanted  to proceed with this to see

what we can get and what  we can't get, and so we have some specific

issues to present to the court.



MS. SAGER: That's fine. And just so that you know, I will(my

interposed objections, if there is a suggestion I can make on how you

could rephrase the question to elicit an answer as opposed to simply

an  objection, if I think the question can be rephrased, I will

suggest that, but it's obviously up to you.



MR. GELBLUM: I will take all the help I can  get. If you want to do

that, too, Dan(



MR. LEONARD: I don't know how to do that.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Okay. Do you understand everything what your attorney just said?



A: Conceptually, yeah.



Q: And, for example, I just asked you a question that prompted

that,which was any conversations you had with Mr. Bailey concerning

the Simpson case.  When I talk about the Simpson case, Iam going to

use some shorthand myself. I mean the circumstances surrounding the

murders of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman. It in-cludes both

the criminal case and thecivil case.



MR. LEONARD: Well, I am going to object to that as vague.



MR. GELBLUM: Okay. Well, I just defined it. You can(fine.



MR. LEONARD: You may think you defined it, but that's vague.



MS. SAGER: There is no question pending.



THE WITNESS: No, I know.



MR. LEONARD: And so therefore I would like a standing objection every

time you use that shorthand term.



