if this was literally true, that it was a different man.



MR. GELBLUM: I will ask whatever you let me ask, which isn't much.



MS. SAGER: Then there is no question pending.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Is it fair to say that he seemed different to you each time you saw

him,



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Vague. Lack of foundation, calls for

speculation.



MS. SAGER: What I think the question is, if I understand it correctly,

is whether you were intending to say that he seemed different as

opposed to that you were actually with a different person.



THE WITNESS: Right.



MS. SAGER: You are not being literally true.



THE WITNESS: Yeah, not being literally true. There was something

subtly different about him each time.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: What?



MS. SAGER: I am not going to let him answer that question for the same

reasons previously stated.



MR. GELBLUM: Okay. Off the record just for a second.



(Discussion held off the record.)



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did you live in the same block as he and  Marquerite?



A: Yes.



Q: For how long?



A: If he moved away in '76, I moved away in  '75 or '74. I know I

moved away in '74-'75. Okay?



Q: Okay.



A: I don't know-'75. I don't know when  he moved away. I've been told

he moved away in '76 or '77. Okay?



Q: You moved away first, anyway. Right?



A: Yes.



Q: So you weren't living on the same block from that point forward.



A: Correct.



Q: So you lived on the same block for how long?



A: Well, Iagain, I built my house in '63, but I don't know when he

moved into his house. I  only met him



Q: During the time



MS. SAGER: The answer is you don't know.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: That's fine.  During the time you were living on the block, did you

ever hear anything about his having beaten his wife?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation, calls for speculation.



MS. SAGER: During the time he lived there from, whatever, '63 to'75?



MR. LEONARD: Leading.



THE WITNESS:No.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did you ever hear about any domestic discord



MS. SAGER: Same objection.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q:between he and Marquerite during that time?



MR. LEONARD: Vague, lack of foundation, leading.



MS. SAGER: Between '63 and '75.



THE WITNESS: No.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did you ever meet-not ever. Prior tolet me start again. While you

were living on the same block  as Mr. Simpson, did you meet Jason or

Arnelle Simpson?



A: Yes.



Q: Did they ever come to your house?



A: My daughter brought them once, yes.They  were children.



Q: How old, approximately?



A: Oh, they would have been like three, four, or something, you know.

I don't remember how old. My daughter was a baby-sitter.



Q: Did you ever meet Nicole Brown Simpson?



A: Never.



Q: I would like to find out, unless your attorney won't let me, in

general terms the process by which the taped interviews were

transformed into the published book. Will you allow him to answer any

questions regarding that process?



MS. SAGER: No, not unless it's been published somewhere.



MR. GELBLUM: Let me just try a few, for example, and make sure that we

are on the same wavelength here.



Q: Who decided which letters to Mr. Simpson would go into the book?



MS. SAGER: Objection.



MR. LEONARD: I object. Lack of foundation,  calls for speculation.



(Discussion held between the Witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



MS. SAGER: Okay. My client informs me that that has been published, so

he can answer that question.



MR. GELBLUM: Good.



MR. LEONARD: Same objection.



THE WITNESS: I made a selection and I brought them to Mr. Simpson,and

he accepted my selection.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Do you know whether his attorneys, any of  his attorneys, had any

involvement in the selectionthe process of selecting the fetters that

were in the book?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Calls for speculation.



MR. GELBLUM: Dan, if the question is, do you  know, that doesn't call

for speculation, which is the question.



MS. SAGER: I am going to object to the question to the extent that it

calls or any unpublished information, but I believe that there has

been information published. In response to that question, I will let

Mr. Schiller reveal that.



THE WITNESS: In my presence his attorneys had nothing to do with it.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Do you know whether they had anything to do with it out of your

presence?



MS. SAGER: Same objection as to the extent there is unpublished

infrmation, but published information you can answer.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Who selected which portions of Mr. Simpson's interviews would be

included in the book?



MS. SAGER: Same objection. To the extent that  there is published

information on it, I will let  Mr. Schiller answer. (Discussion held

between the witness and counsel outside the hearing of the reporter.)



MS. SAGER: You can answer that.



THE WITNESS: I made the total selection.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Without anybody else's input?



MS. SAGER: Same objection. To the extent there is published

information, I will let Mr. Schiller answer that.



MR. LEONARD: Well, Inever mind.



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



THE WITNESS: Me and members of my editorial  staff.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did any of Mr. Simpson's attorneys have any input into deciding

which interviews would be included in the book?



MS. SAGER: Same objection. I will let him answer to the extent that

that information has been publicly revealed.



THE WITNESS: None whatsoever.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Where was that information publicly revealed?



A: I've said a couple times on television shows and so forth that Mr.

Simpson's attorneys had nothing to do with the writig of the book, and

I made the total decisions.



Q: Are the



A: Excuse me a second.



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



THE WITNESS: Yes.



MS. SAGER: He has already answered the question, so... BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Are the words that are attributed to Mr. Simpson in the book I WANT

TO TELL YOU verbatim transcripts of the interviews?



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: I don't mean complete, but is every word that's printed in here

something coming from Mr. Simpson, something that he actually said?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Compound, overbroad.



MS. SAGER: To the extent you can answer that question without looking

at it, I will let you answer  it, but...



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



THE WITNESS: No person speaks in perfect  English that you can read,

and sometimes people use  the same word in a sentence many, many

times. So all  of the material is exactly what he said, but it has 

been made readable so it can be consumed and disseminated in a

literary form. So in some instances he may have used in a paragraph

the same word five times or four times, and I may have looked up in

the thesaurus other words that were more apropos.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: More apropos of what?



A: From a reading point of view.



Q: It sounded better to your ear?



A: Or that might be better to a reader, a  reader's ear. When you

read, you don't hear.  Sometimes you hear yourself reading, yes, okay,

but, you knowso the grammar, the structure, has been  made readable,

but it is what he said.



MS. SAGER: I think that answers question. Sounds like it's a no, not

verbatim.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: So the substance of everythingyou didn't change the substance of

anything.



A: That's correct.



Q: Did you ever discuss with Mr. Simpson his whereabouts on the

evening of June 12, 1994?



MS. SAGER: Same objection to the extent that  information is not

published. If that information has been publicly disseminated, I will

let Mr. Schiller answer to the extent that it has been.



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Leading.



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



MS. SAGER: We are not aware of any published  information that answers

that question. If it's out there, then he would answer it, but we are

not aware of any, so the objection stands.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did you ever discuss with Mr. Simpson any of his activities from

June 12, 1994 through June 17, 1994?



MS. SAGER: Same objection.



MR. LEONARD: Same objection.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Are you aware of any published material regarding any of that time

period, your discussions with him during that time period?



A: No.



Q: Upon Mr. Simpson's release from jail, you  took some pictures of

him. Correct?



A: That is correct.



Q: And some of those pictures have been published?



A: Yes.



Q: Did you take pictures of Mr. Simpson within a month after his

release from jail anywhere other than at Rockingham?



MS. SAGER: I am going to object to the question to the extent it calls

for any unpublished  photographs or material that Mr. Schiller

gathered for the future publication. To the extent there is published

information, I will let him answer that question.



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



THE WITNESS: The answer is yes.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Yes? Where?



MS. SAGER: And again, only as to published  photographs.



THE WITNESS: The residence of Don Ohlmeyer; a  golf course in Panama

City, Florida; my hotel room in  Panama City, Florida; the beach in

Panama City, Florida. Various locations in Panama City Florida.  There

may have been one other location, but I don't remember specifically. I

have some images in my mind,  but I don't remember exactly where, but

it's in that period of time.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: And did you take pictures of  Mr. Simpson's children during this

time frame also?



MS. SAGER: Same objection. To the extent the information is published,

I will let Mr. Schiller answer it.



THE WITNESS: His older children.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Did you take any pictures of his younger children after



A: Never.



Q: Have you taken any pictures of Mr. Simpson's younger children, that

is, Sydney and Justin, since Mr. Simpson's acquittal?



MS. SAGER: Same objection to the extent the  information is

unpublished.



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of the reporter.)



THE WITNESS: I have not photographed the children, the younger

children. That information has been published.



MR. LEONARD: Do you mean that the fact that  you have not photographed

them



THE WITNESS: Yes.



MR. LEONARD:has been published?



THE WITNESS: Yes.



MR. LEONARD: Because I didn't



MS. SAGER: The fact that he has not



MR. LEONARD: Okay. Take a break?



(Discussion held off the record.)



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Were the photographs that you took of  Mr. Simpson and his older

children after his release from jail pursuant to a written agreement

that Polaris Communications entered into with American Media?



MS. SAGER: To the extent that information is  public, I will let Mr.

Schiller answer it. Otherwise I will object on the same ground.



THE WITNESS: Yes.



(Discussion held between the witness and counsel outside the hearing

of  the reporter.)



THE WITNESS: Okay.



MS. SAGER: You are talking about the publication of the photographs? I

missed the question. I'm sorry. Was the publication pursuant  to? Is

that what you said?



THE WITNESS: Then my answer is yes.



MR. GELBLUM: Did he take them pursuant to.



THE WITNESS: Did I take them pursuant to, the answer is yes.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Are you aware of whether Mr. Simpson has ever taken a lie detector

test in relation to the murders of Ron Goldman and Nicole Brown

Simpson?



MS. SAGER: Same objection. Instruct the witness not to answer unless

there is published information one way or the other.



MR. GELBLUM: What's your definition of  "published" for these

purposes?



MS. SAGER: If Mr. Schiller has information that he has publicly

revealed, then he has published that information, and he can't assert

the privilege as to information he has already revealed.



MR. GELBLUM: But only if he has publicly  revealed it?



MS. SAGER: Right. Because he is the one who  holds the privilege,

so... And as to anything, if  it's published information or something

that's been  revealed by Mr. Schiller, I will let him answer as to 

that, so I don't need to keep saying that.



MR. GELBLUM: Well, I assume your objection was only if he had some

informationif he had obtained some information, if there was any, in

the course of  gathering information or dissemination to the public.



MS. SAGER: Correct.



BY MR. GELBLUM:



Q: Okay. Other than in the course of gathering information for

dissemination to the public, have you ever learned any information

about Mr. Simpson having taken a lie detector test regarding the

murders of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ron Goldman?



A: No.



MR. GELBLUM: Why don't we take a break to  change paper, and when we

go back on, we are going to  have to do it under seal, because there

are going to be documents fromthese are the contracts.



(Recess.)



(The remainder of the transcript is confidendal pursuant to the

protective order and is bound separately.) </PRE> <HR WIDTH=525

