HREF="/map/casefiles.map"><IMG

SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/casefiles.gif" ISMAP ALT="Court TV

Casefiles" BORDER="0"></A> <BR CLEAR=ALL> <P>Jason Simpson, O.J.

Simpson's son from his first marriage, denied in this May 8, 1996

deposition that his father engaged in domestic violence. But at one point in the criminal trial,

considering the prosecution's evidence, he recalled, "the thought

crossed [his] mind" that his father might be responsible for Nicole

Brown Simpson's death. Simpson said he never questioned his father

about the murders. But he said he is confident that his father is

innocent.</p><HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT> <PRE>





SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA



FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES



SHARON RUFO, Plaintiff vs.



ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, Defendants



DEPOSITION OF JASON LAMAR SIMPSON Los Angeles, California May 8, 1996



DAVID S COLEMAN CSR #4813 JOB NO 981370



SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS

ANGELES



SHARON RUFO, Plaintiff,



vs.



ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPS0N, Defendants.



FREDRIC GOLDMAN, etc., et al., Plaintiffs



vs.



ORENTIHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al., Defendants.



LOUIS H. BROWN, etc., Plaintiffs,



vs.



ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, defendant



. Videotaped deposition of JASON LAMAR SIMPSON, taken on behalf of the

Plaintiffs, at 11377 West Olympic Boulevard, 10th Floor, Los Angeles,

California, commencing at 9:45a.m., on Wednesday, May 8, 1996, before

David S. Coleman, CSR #4813, pursuant to Subpoena



APPEARANCES:



FOR THE PLAINTIFFS FREDRIC GOLDMAN, ET AL.: MITCHELL, SILBERBERG &

KNUPP BY DANIEL M. PETROCELLI, ESQ 11377 West Olympic Boulevard Sixth

Floor Los Angeles, California 90064-1683



FOR THE PLAINTIFF ESTATE OF BROWN: JOHN QUINLAN KELLY, ESQ 330 Madison

Avenue New York, New York 7-5090 (212) 682-1700 (Of record but not

present) -and- NATASHA ROIT, ESQ. 116 North Robertson Boulevard Suite

705 Los Angeles, California 90048



FOR THE PLAINTIFF SHARON RUFO HORNBERGER & CRISWELL 444 South Flower

Street Thirty First Floor Los Angeles, California 90071 (Of record but

not present)



FOR THE DEFENDANT ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON AND THE WITNESS: BAILEY,

FISHMAN & LEONARD BY DANIEL LEONARD, ESQ 66 Long Wharf Boston,

Massachusetts 02110 (817) 723-1980 -and- BAKER, SILBERBERG & KEENER

2850 Ocean Park Boulevard Suite 300 Santa Monica, California

90405-2936 (Of record but not present) -and- ROBERT D. BLASIER, ESQ.

6355 Riverside Boulevard Suite 2-F Sacramento, California 95831 (916)

427-1600 (Of record but not present)



ALSO PRESENT FREDRIC GOLDMAN



INDEX WITNESS JASON LAMAR SIMPSON Examination by Petrocelli 8, 361

Examination by Ms Roit 347 EXHIBITS 181 Handwritten document 182

Handwritten document 183 Map of 360 N. Rockingham with handwritten

markings 184 Deposition Subpoena and Production of Documents and

Things of Jason Simpson dated February 5,1996





THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Good morning. Here begins videotape No. 1 in the

deposition of Jason Simpson in the consolidated cases of Fredric

Goldman, Sharon Rufo  and Louis Brown vs. Orenthal James Simpson in

the Superior Court, State of California, County of Los Angeles, the

lead case number of which is SC 031947.



Today's date is Wednesday, May 8th, 1996. The time is approximately

9:46. This deposition is being taken at 11377 West Olympic Boulevard

in Los Angeles, California, and was made at the request of plaintiff

of the Law Offices of Mitchell, Silberberg & Knupp.



The videographer is Rod Rigole, employed by Coleman, Haas, Martin and

Schwab of Los Angeles, California.



Would counsel please identify yourselves and state whom you represent.



MR. PETROCELLI: Daniel Petrocelli for  Plaintiff Fredric Goldman.



MS. ROIT: Natasha Roit for Plaintiff Brown.



MR. LEONARD: Daniel Leonard for O.J. Simpson  and the witness, Jason

Simpson.



JASON LAMAR SIMPSON, having been first duly sworn, was examined and

testified as follows:



EXAMINATION BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Good morning, Mr. Simpson. My name is Daniel Petrocelli, and I

represent one of the plaintiffs in this lawsuit against O.J. Simpson.

I represent Fredric Goldman.



You are here to give a deposition in this lawsuit. You've been put

under oath by the court  reporter, and that means you are obligated to

tell the truth just like you were testifying in a court of law.



Do you understand that?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: And that means that you're subject to the same penalties of perjury

just as though you were  testifying in a court of law.



Do you understand that?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: And you understand that deliberately  lying under oath is a felony

under California law for which you can go to prison.



Do you understand that?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. Have you ever been examined under oath before?



A: No, not that I recall. Not that I recall.



Q: Well, are you unsure whether you've given testimony under oath?



A: Yeah, I'm not sure.



Q: Can you describe to me some proceedings  when you think you may

have testified under oath but are not sure?



A: Yeah. A court case I had gotten into, I got in a car accident a

while back, and I don't -- I'm not sure if I swore in or anything like

that. I just  remember going to court and taking care of the matter.



Q: Okay. Let me --



A: It wasn't a trial or anything like that.



Q: Okay. Let me mention a couple of things  just so we can get a clean

record. Let me finish my  question before you answer, and I will try

not to interrupt you.



A: Okay.



Q: This is to make the reporter's job easy,  because he can only,

despite his extraordinary  abilities, get only one person down at a

time.



A: Okay.



Q: Secondly, your voice has a tendency to trail off near the end of

your sentences, and if you could keep your voice up so that everybody

can hear, and also so that we can tell when you've completed your

answer.



A: Okay



Q: Okay? Rather than kind of mumbling near the end, just try to give a

complete answer.



A: Okay.



Q: You were in an automobile accident, and  the case went to court and

you gave testimony?



A: Yes.



Q: Was that a trial?



A: No.



Q: Was it in a courtroom?



A: Yes.



Q: Was there a judge there?



A: Yes.



Q: A jury?



A: No.



Q: Okay. And when was that?



A: Last summer, I believe.



Q: Summer of 1995?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Who sued you?



A: I forgot her name. Olga Klavaris or something like that.



Q: Over what?



A: A car accident. I ran into her.



Q: Okay. Were you under the influence of alcohol?



A: No, sir.



Q: Were you under the influence of drugs?



A: No, sir.



Q: Was anyone injured?



A: No, sir.



Q: Just property damage?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. Is that the only time you've been involved in an automobile

accident?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. Have you ever been convicted of a crime?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. Tell me what crimes you've been  convicted of.



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object, unless you can lay a foundation

under the rule. You can ask him if it was a felony. You are going to

lay a foundation for that?



MR. PETROCELLI: I want to know all crimes that he's been convicted of.



MR.LEONARD: Well, I don't think you have a right to ask for anything

other than felonies.



MR. PETROCELLI: Well, it may lead to discoverable -- felony

convictions are admissible --



MR. LEONARD: Right.



MR. PETROCELLI: -- but other convictions may or may not be, but they

may lead to discoverable evidence.



MR. LEONARD: Well, I am going to instruct him not to answer other than

felony convictions.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Have you been convicted of crimes other than felonies? You can

answer that yes or no.



A: I wasn't quite sure exactly what it was.  It wasn't a felony.



Q: It was not a felony.



A: No.



Q Was it something that you pled guilty to?



A: No.



Q: Was it something that you were found  guilty of after a trial?



A: No.



MR. PETROCELLI: What are we talking about, Mr. Leonard?



MR. LEONARD: Go ahead. Ask him.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Okay. Tell us what you have in mind.



A: I got DUI. I don't know what that is, though. What's that?



Q: Driving under the influence?



A: Yeah. I don't know what thing that goes  under.



Q: Okay. Let me see if I can find out what we're talking about here.

You were charged with driving under the influence?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: What year was that?



A: I think I was 17, so it must have been -- or 18. It might have been

1988, '89.



Q: How old are you?



A: I'm 26.



Q: When were you born?



A: 1970.



Q: What's your birthday?



A: April 21st.



Q: What year did the DUI occur?



A: I think it was maybe in 1989.



Q: Were you involved in an automobile accident at that time?



A: Uh-uh.



THE REPORTER: No?



THE WITNESS: No.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: That's another rule. You have to --



A: I understand.



Q: -- give an audible response.



A: I forgot. Sorry.



Q: That's all right. Was this a charge brought against you by the City

of Los Angeles?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: And what was the disposition of that charge?



A: I don't understand the question, "disposition of that charge."



Q: Were you found guilty or what?



A: Yeah. Yeah.



Q: Was there a trial?



A: No, there wasn't a trial.



Q: How were you found guilty?



A: What did I do? It's a while ago. I'm trying to remember. I remember

going to court and --



Q: Did you testify?



A: No.



Q: Was there a jury?



A: No.



Q: Did your lawyer plead guilty on your behalf?



A: I don't remember



Q: Make a deal?



A: Yeah, I believe so.



Q: Okay. Did you serve any time?



A: No. No.



Q: Community service?



A: Yes.



Q: How many hours?



A: 30 hours, I think, community service and AA meetings, and what

else.



Q: Did you attend the AA meetings?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: And did you perform the community  service?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. Is that the only time that you've ever been charged with a

DUI?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Is that the only time you've ever been charged with a crime?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. You ever been sued for anything else in your life?



A: Other than --



Q:  You mentioned the -- excuse me. Was the automobile accident

litigation? Did that result in litigation, the one this past summer?



A: What do you mean? Did it --



Q: I don't -- did someone sue you?



A: Yeah, she started to, but I guess she dropped it.



Q: She dropped it?



A: Yeah.



Q: Was there a settlement?



A: No.



Q: She just dropped the case?



A: Dropped the case.



Q: And you gave us the name of the  plaintiff?



A: Olga something.



Q: Olga?



A: I don't remember what her last name was.



Q: Against Jason Simpson?



A: Uh-huh.



Q: You have to answer.



A: Yes.



Q: Where was that case filed?



A: Los Angeles.



Q: Who represented you in that case?



A: I forgot the lawyer's name. Carl Jones.



Q: Private practictioner?



A: Yes.



Q: Who represented you in the DUI case?



A: I forgot his name. It was a long time ago.



Q: Was that a public defender?



A: No



Q: A private lawyer?



A: Uh-huh.



Q: You have to answer yes.



A: Yes.



Q: Okay. And have you ever been sued either criminally or civilly in

any other proceeding?



A: No, sir.



Q: Okay. Isn't it true that you were -- that charges were brought

against you by the City of  Los Angeles for assault on a guy named

Goldberg at a restaurant?



A: Yes. Yes, sir. I forgot about that, but I wasn't sued.



Q: Charges were brought against you for assault. True?



A: Right. Right.



Q: You didn't tell us about that earlier.



A: I totally forgot about that.



Q: Okay. Well, it's crucial that you not forget --



A: Okay.



Q: -- and that you try to give it your best in answering these

questions.



A: Okay.



Q: This was a case brought against you by  the People of the State of

California in January of  1993. Correct?



A: Yes.



Q: And you assaulted a man named Paul Goldberg. Correct?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: At Revival Cafe restaurant in Los Angeles. Right?



A: Yes, sir.



Q And you pled guilty to this. True?



A: No, sir.



Q: What was the outcome?



A: The -- I had to -- what I had to do?



Q: Did you plead nolo contendere or no contest?



A: No contest.



Q: Okay. What was the sentence you received?



A: Community service.



Q: Was that all?



A: That's it.



Q: How many hours?



A: I don't remember.



