Ron Goldman?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object. Lack of foundation.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Go ahead.



A: No.



Q: Did she ever discuss with you any persons that she was seeing as

friends or dating as friends in  the last few months of her life?



A: No, sir.



Q: Now, you said you last saw Nicole -- first of all, you said you

last saw her when she had pneumonia. Then you said, when I asked you

the  question about Sydney's -- about Justin's graduation,  that it

must have been on that occasion that you last  saw Nicole.



Do you recall that?



A: Yeah, you reminded me.



Q: Okay. So it's now your recollection that you last saw Nicole at

Justin's graduation at the  Sunshine School?



A: I believe that was the last time.



Q: And when you went to that event who did  you go with?



A: I went by myself.



Q: Did you get tickets to go there?



A: You didn't need a ticket for it.



Q: Who was there on behalf of your brother  Justin?



A: My sister Arnelle, I don't know if Sydney was there, and Nicole was

there.



Q: Did you go out afterwards?



A: No, I didn't. I think they went back to the house. I'm not sure.

I'm not sure if I weft with  them back to the house.



Q: Which house?



A: Back to Bundy, I think, but --



Q: Where did you go?



A: I know I had to work, so I couldn't spend the rest of the day with

them. I wanted to.



Q: Which day was this?



A: The day of the graduation.



Q: Why did you want to spend the rest of the day with them?



A: Because I love them.



Q: Who is "them"?



A: Sydney, Justin, Nicole.



Q: Do you know what they did after they left  the graduation?



A: No, I don't remember.



Q: Do you know if they went to dinner?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation, asking him to speculate.



THE WITNESS: Actually, it was early still.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: In the afternoon?



A: Yeah. So, no, they didn't go out to dinner.



Q: Were you disappointed your father was not  there?



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



THE WITNESS: I actually didn't really -- since Nicole told me that he

was at some business thing he had to take care of, I really didn't

think too much of it.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: It was not uncommon for your father to miss family functions

because of business. Correct?



A: Correct.



Q: He was gone a lot. Right?



A: Correct.



Q: And that was through -- that was true throughout your lifetime as

well. Correct?



A: Correct.



Q: And that continued to be true all the way up until Nicole's death.

Correct?



A: Correct.



Q: So he missed lots of family functions involving you. Right?



A: Yes.



Q: And involving Sydney and Justin. Right?



A: Sydney and Justin, I don't know so much  because I wasn't really

there, but I'm sure he missed his share.



Q: A lot with you. Right?



A: Yeah. I mean, yeah, he was working a lot.



Q: Out of town?



A: Yeah.



Q: Played golf a lot?



A: Played golf every morning, but I wasn't up that early anyway, so...



Q: Went out of town on golf tournaments a lot, celebrity tournaments

--



A: Not --



Q: -- golfing for Hertz, those sorts of things?



MR. LEONARD: Object to the compound nature of  the question.



Q: You can answer it if -- you can try.



THE WITNESS: He didn't play golf when I lived  at home.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: What was your relationship with O.J. Simpson like?



A: What was it like?



Q: Yes.



A: At what point?



Q: Did it ever change?



A: Well, I mean, it's matured.



Q: Other than matured as you became older and he, too, did you have a

good relationship with him throughout your life, or did you have a --



A: Yeah, I mean --



Q: -- bad relationship with him at times?



A: At times.



Q: Did you have any falling-outs?



A: At times.



Q: What times?



A: I don't know. When I was 16 and wanted  to get a car right away.

What else. When I wanted my  own room further away from the house. He

won every  time.



Q: These are less specific little incidents where you had arguments?



A: Yeah. I mean, I've argued with my dad.



Q: But other than normal father-son arguments, your testimony is that

you've had a very  strong relationship with him since day one?



A: I think so. Well, now, looking back, I mean, since everything

that's happened it's gotten  stronger, so in my opinion it's like I

start to  realize it is a lot stronger now than it was before.



Q: What was your opinion as of June of 1994?



A: Of our relationship?



Q: Yes.



A: I mean, I didn't have any problems with  it.



Q: Was he there for you all the time?



A: Yeah.



Q: Okay. Did he ever beat you?



A: No.



Q: Never?



A: Beat me? No.



Q: Yes, beat you.



A: No.



Q: Did he ever hit you?



A: I've gotten a whipping on the butt before  with his belt when I was

a kid.



Q: Nothing that you would regard now, looking back, as abusive?



A: No.



Q: Okay. Did he ever strike you with anything other than his hands?



A: No. He's never stricken me with his hands, though.



Q: How has he hit you when he --



A: I told you, with a belt on my butt.



Q: Just a belt?



A: Yeah.



Q: Once or twice?



A: I don't know. I kinda -- kinda messed around a lot when I was a

kid. No, I don't know.  Maybe 10, 20 times. I don't remember exactly.



Q: When was the last time?



A: I don't remember.



Q: Small kid?



A: I was about 14 maybe. It was not too long before Nicole and my

dad's wedding, which I think was in '85.



Q: Did he ever inflict serious injuries upon you?



A: Never.



Q: Did you ever have to get medical treatment as a result of a

beating?



A: No, sir.



Q: Did you ever go to the hospital or the doctor as a result of being

hit by your dad?



A: No, sir.



Q: Were you afraid of him?



A: No.



Q: Okay. Did you ever see him in a rage?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object to that as  vague.



THE WITNESS: No, not in a rage. I -- wouldn't  characterize it as a

rage.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Did you ever see him in what you would characterize as somebody out

of control?



A: Out of control, no.



Q: Did you ever see him throw things around?



A: No, I've never seen him throw things.



Q: Never saw him throw anything?



A: No. I saw him throw a football, saw him throw a tennis ball.



Q: Never saw him throw any item or article in anger?



A: No, I've never seen him throw an article.



Q: Like photographs or a glass or anything  like that?



A: I've never seen him do that.



Q: Okay. Have you seen him get mad?



A: Yeah.



Q: Have you seen him get really mad?



A: Yeah.



Q: Have you ever seen him, when he got  really mad, pick up a glass

and throw it?



A: No.



Q: You ever see him get so mad that he actually hurt himself, cut

himself?



A: No.



Q: You ever see him take a baseball bat to anything?



A: No.



Q: You ever see him break down a door or break -- or put his fist

through a wall?



A: No, sir.



Q: Anything like that?



A: No, sir.



Q: So in your opinion, based on your experience living with your

father and knowing him all  these years, he was in total control of

his emotions and temper. Is that true?



A: I never said that.



Q: Answer that question.



A: I said I've never seen him do anything like that.



Q: So you've never seen him lose control of  himself. Right?



A: No, sir.



Q: And you've always seen him in control of  himself. True?



A: Yeah. I've seen him upset, but he was in  control.



Q: When he -- when you've seen him upset, how did he behave?



A: Angry.



Q: And did that manifest itself in any physical way?



A: Arguing.



Q: Just arguing?



A: Yeah. Maybe raising his voice, pacing.



Q: Veins in his neck bulge or pop?



A: I don't know about the veins.



Q: Or his eyes start to bulging?



A: Yeah, yeah, I've seen that.



Q: When he was angry at you?



A: A couple times.



Q: Did he ever threaten to hit you?



A: Yeah. I mean, yeah, if I don't get up to  my room, "Get up to your

room," or something like that. I mean --



Q: Did he ever threaten to hit you in such a  way that you were really

afraid for your life?



A: Well, any time he threatened me -- not for my life, no.



Q: Not for your life.



A: Hell, no. Sorry. Excuse me. No.



Q: Did he ever threaten you with anything  other than a spanking?



A: No. Or punishment.



Q: Or punishment.



A: No.



Q: Okay. Did you ever see him on drugs?



A: No.



Q: Did you ever see him take drugs?



A: No.



Q: You ever been in the same room when he took drugs?



A: No, sir.



Q: Did you ever take any drugs?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object to that --



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You can answer.



MR. LEONARD: -- and instruct him not to answer.



BY MR PETROCELLI:



[Portion Deleted]





Q: Okay. Did you ever see your father get  angry at another person

other than yourself?



A: Yeah. Yes.



Q: Who?



A: My sister, Nicole, my mom, I think a guy  that ran over our dog

once a long time ago; tried to get away with it.



Q: What did your father do in that incident  with the dog?



A: I think he yelled at the guy. That's all. Guy tried to get away.



Q: Did you ever see O.J. Simpson strike  somebody?



A: No. I got a picture of him hitting somebody -- that's about it --

in a football game.



Q: I don't mean in professional sports or college sports or any

sporting activity. I mean in  anger, in a fight, losing his temper or

being provoked or whatever.



Did you ever see him strike another person other than when he spanked

you?



A: No.



Q: Never?



A: Never.



Q: Never saw him hit Marquerite, your mother?



A: No.



Q: Did he?



A: Not that I know of.



Q: Did she ever tell you that he did?



A: No.



Q: Did anybody ever tell you that he did?



A: No. No.



Q: Did the police ever come out to the house  when you lived -- when

he lived with Marquerite and  you?



A: Not that I ever remember.



Q: You have no knowledge and no information about anything like that.

Is that true?



A: If he hit my mother, he'd know.



Q: How would he know?



A: Because nobody hit my mother.



Q: Nobody ever did.



A: No. If anybody ever hit my mother believe me, they'd know about it.



Q: From you?



A: Hell, yeah.



Q: Including your father?



A: Yes.



Q: That would be unacceptable to you. Right?



A: Very.



Q: Just because she's your mother or because it's unacceptable to hit

another woman?



A: Both reasons.



Q: And would it also be unacceptable to you if he ever hit Nicole?



A: Yes.



Q: And you would find that totally outrageous and wrong on his part.

Right?



A: Yes.



Q: Did you ever see him hit Nicole?



A: No.



Q: Ever?



A: No, sir.



Q: Did you ever -- were you ever told by  anyone that he struck or hit

Nicole?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object to that as --



MR. PETROCELLI: Why?



MR.LEONARD: -- lack of foundation.



Told by anyone?



MR. PETROCELLI: Yes, by anyone.



THE WITNESS: I was never personally told that  he hit Nicole.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: What do you mean, "personally"?



A: No one ever said, "Jason, your dad hit  Nicole" or "O.J. hit

Nicole."



Q: Did Nicole ever tell you that?



A: No, Nicole never did.



Q: Did Arnelle ever tell you that?



A: Arnelle never did.



Q: Did Mr. Simpson, O.J. Simpson, ever tell  you that?



A: No, he never did.



Q: Did Al Cowlings ever tell you that?



A: No, he never did either.



Q: Did anyone ever tell you that?



A: No one ever personally ever told me that he did.



Q: Did you ever overhear a conversation where someone said O.J.

Simpson hit Nicole?



A: On TV.



Q: When on TV?



A: I don't know. During the trial, on the HARD COPY shows and stuff

like that.



Q: Is that the first time -- Strike that. You heard this on TV after

Nicole's  murder for the first time. Is that right?



A: That he hit Nicole?



Q: Yes.



A: Yeah.



Q: First time you ever heard it. Right?



A: Yeah.



Q: Never heard it in 1989 when you were 19 years old.



A: That's -- no. I heard they got in  fight. I never heard that he hit

Nicole.



Q: What did you hear about the fight in  1989?



A: That they got --



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object unless you  can lay a foundation.



MR. PETROCELLI: I just asked him, what did he hear about it.



MR. LEONARD: Yeah, why don't you ask him where he heard it and when he

heard it and who he heard it.



Is that the way you want the record?



MR. PETROCELLI: Yes.



MR.LEONARD: Okay, great, go ahead.



THE WITNESS: What was that?



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: What did you hear about the fight in  1989?



A: I got a phone call, and my father told me that he and Nicole had

gotten in a fight, and he  wanted to tell me because he's probably

gonna -- I was  probably gonna hear about it in the paper or something

 like that.



Q: And when did you get that phone call?



A: I think it was either New Year's Eve or  New Year's Day. New Year's

 Day.



Q: 1989?



A: Yeah. Because the Rose Bowl was on the 2nd that day. It wasn't on

the 1st. It's usually on  the 1st.



Q: How do you remember that?



A: Because he called me at the hotel. I was getting ready to go --



Q: What hotel?



A: -- to the Rose Bowl. I can't remember the name of it. We stayed in

a hotel before football games at USC. It's on Wilshire. I think it's

-- I don't know the name of it.



Q: So you think on January 2, 1989 your father --



A: No. January 1, it would have been.



Q: Why? You stayed in the hotel overnight?



A: Yeah, you stayed before the game.



Q: Who?



A: The team.



Q: You were on the team?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. And he called -- You were a freshman?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. And you were part of the SC varsity squad?



A: SC football team, yeah.



Q: On the football team.



A: Yes, sir.



Q: And he called you at the hotel where the USC football team was

staying on January 1, 1989 to inform you that he and Nicole had gotten

into a fight.



A: Yes.



Q: And where was he, if you know, when he made this phone call to you?



A: I don't know.



Q: Did you ask him?



A: No. I was kinda upset.



Q: What did he say to you had happened?



A: He said, "Look, we got into a fight.  You're probably gonna read

about it. I just wanted to tell you because I don't want you to find

out reading  in the paper."



Q: What about that upset you?



A: The fact that they got in a fight. I knew that it must have been a

pretty big fight if it's  gonna make it to the paper.



Q: Well, he had gotten into fights with  Nicole before. Right?



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You had seen them argue before. Right?



A: I've heard them argue, yeah, seen them  argue.



Q: So what about this particular account of  his fight with Nicole

upset you?



A: The fact that he called me to tell me, to warn me that for some

reason I should know about this particular fight because -- I don't

know -- because, "You might find out from somebody else." I knew that

for some reason it must have been something severe about the fight.



Q: Now you say "for some reason."  In fact, he told you much more than

that. Correct?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Argumentative.



THE WITNESS: No. He told me just what I told  you.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: He told you that the police had come out  to the house, for

example. Correct?



A: No, he never said that. He just said, "We got into a fight."



Q: He said, "I want you to know we got in a  fight and it may be in

the newspapers," and that's all  he said. Is that your testimony?



A: Basically, yes.



Q: Okay. He didn't tell you, "We got into a fight, and Nicole got

hurt." Did he say that?



A: I don't remember him saying that.



Q: Did he say that Nicole had marks on her face or bruises?



A: He didn't get into detail.



Q: Did he say that the fight was a physical fight?



A: No, he didn't get -- he didn't even say that, I don't think.



Q: So as far as you knew --



A: He was pretty vague.



Q: -- it might have been just an argument. Right?



A: He was pretty vague. No, I knew it wasn't just an argument because

arguments don't make it to the news paper.



Q: You knew this was a physical altercation. True?



A: It had to be.



Q: And he told you it was. Right?



A: Either that or the fact that the police must have found out or a

neighbor must have found out or somebody must have found out in order

for the newspapers to be alarmed by it. I mean, why would the 

newspapers print a fight between my father and my stepmom.



Q: Unless something serious happened.  Right?



A: Yeah. I mean, it didn't take, you know, Einstein to figure that

out.



Q: So you understood something really serious had happened. Right?



A: Something serious must have happened.



Q: And did you ask him, "What, Dad, happened?"



A: No, I didn't.



Q: Did you ask him if Nicole was okay?



A: I don't remember.



Q: Did you call Nicole to find out if she was okay?



A: I saw her the next day or two days later.



Q: After the Rose Bowl?



A: Yeah.



Q: Did you ask her at that time?



A: If she was all right?



A: Yes.



A: Yeah.



Q: So from the moment your father called you  on January 1 to tell you

about his fight with Nicole the time you saw her a couple of days

later, you  did not speak to Nicole at all. True?



A: No. True.



Q: Never once called her to see if she was okay. True?



A: She wasn't home. I didn't know where she was.



Q: I didn't ask you that. You didn't call her. Right?



A: No. I called the house. She wasn't home.



Q: You did call the house.



A: Yeah.



Q: How many times?



A: I think a couple times.



Q: Okay. From where?



A: I think my dorm room, maybe somebody  else's room.



Q: What days did you call the house?



A: I think the 2nd -- or not the 2nd. The 3rd and the 4th.



Q: So you didn't call on the 1st, and you didn't call on the 2nd.

True?



A: No. I found out the 1st at night.



Q: Right.



A: And I didn't call on the 2nd, no.



Q: Okay.



A: And the 3rd is the day I'm guessing I probably called, and I think

I saw her on the 4th.



Q: Okay. Did you -- can you remember specifically calling her on the

3rd?



A: No.



Q: And when you spoke to her on the 4th, was it over the telephone or

in person?



A: I said, "...I think I saw her on the 4th."



Q: Where did you see her on January 4?



A: It was the house.



Q: Whose house?



A: My dad's house and her house.



Q: You went over there?



A: Yeah.



Q: And did you talk to her about the fight?



A: Yeah. I said, "What happened? How are  you?"



Q: When you said, "What happened," what did she say?



A: She was like -- I didn't see her. It wasn't like face to face. She

was kinda like far  away, and she was pretty upset, and from my best 

recollection, I mean, she was up -- she was just  walking around, and

I asked her if she was all right,  and she was just like (Sound).



She didn't really say anything about it and I knew she was upset, and

I just asked her, "Look, can I borrow the Bronco?" She didn't want to

talk to me either, it seemed.



Q: Describe the marks and injuries that you saw on her.



A: I didn't see any marks or injuries on her.



Q: Nothing?



A: No, because I wasn't this close to her.



Q: How close were you?



A: I was -- she was probably about mid table, but --



Q: Like 15, 20 feet?



A: 15, 20 feet, yeah, but it was in the kitchen, and I couldn't tell

if she was -- I mean, in  retrospect it was like she didn't -- it was

like she  was acting like she didn't want me to see.



Q: Do you carried on a conversation with her  from a distance of 15 to

20 feet. Is that what you're  saying?



A: Yeah, but we weren't talking to each  other  me and you are talking

to each other right  now.



Q: Who were you talking to?



A: What do you mean? There was no mistaken  who I was talking to. I'm

saying just because I look like this (indicating) doesn't mean I'm not

talking to  Mr. Petrocelli. I may not be looking at you, but I'm 

still talking to you.



Q: What I am trying to find out is this:  You went into the house, and

you went and you saw her there. Right?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: And you asked her how she was what had happened, et cetera. Right?



A: I didn't really get into what had happened right away. It just kind

of --



Q: But you told me just a few minutes ago --



A: -- blurted out.



Q: -- you said, "What happened?" that what you said?



A: I think.



Q: Okay. And you're telling me that for however long you and she

conversed, it was conducted at a distance of 15 to 20 feet, and you

got no closer  to her at that time. Is that your testimony? Yes or 

no.



A: Yes.



Q: Okay. Did you ask Nicole why she didn't  want to see you or to be

with you or even to talk to  you?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. I think that's misstating his testimony. Plus

it's a compound question.



Go ahead. You can answer it.



THE WITNESS: She never said, "I didn't want to see you." She wanted to

be left alone.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: How do you know that?



A: Just in knowing Nicole.



Q: What did she say to indicate that to you?



A: She didn't say. She didn't really want to be bothered.



Q: Did you try to get closer to her to look at her?



A: Kinda, yeah.



Q: What stopped you?



A: Her moving away.



Q: She ran away from you?



A: I didn't say run. I said move.



Q: Where did she move?



A: She was kinda pacing around, being fidgety all in the kitchen.



Q: Did you go up to her to hug her?



A: I kinda moved a little bit closer, but it wasn't a hug kind of --

it wasn't a real emotional type of thing. She was very standoff-ish.

She was  upset. I mean, she was upset about the whole  situation, I

guess.



Q: And that's the only conversation you ever had with her about this

fight on New Year's Day?



A: Yeah.



Q: Did you ever ask her again?



A: About?



Q: Was she trying to avoid showing you her face, based on your

observations?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Calls for speculation.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You can tell when a person is trying not  to show you their face

such as if I'm talking to you now, I'm turning my head away

(indicating).



Did she make any movements to you to  indicate that she really didn't

want you to see her  face?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Calls for  speculation.



Go ahead.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You may answer.



A: I don't know.



Q: You don't know.



A: No, I don't know.



Q: It's fair to say that you love your father?



A: Yes.



Q: Fair to say that you don't want to see him lose this case?



A: I wouldn't want to see him lose it, no.



Q: And is it fair to say that even if a jury were to conclude that he

killed Nicole and he killed Ron, you would stand by his side?



A: It would be kinda hard.



Q: You wouldn't abandon him, would you?



A: It would be really hard. He's my father, but...



Q: You're loyal to your father. Right?



A: Yes.



Q: And you don't want to hurt him in this case, do you?



A: No. I mean...



