A: I just think she -- she ran with a suspect crowd, and just being

around there and being around Nicole and even have the kids around it,

it's  just -- it's just -- it seems too fishy. She's just fishy.



Q: Is that the extent of your conversation  with Arnelle?



A: The extent of the conversation?



Q: Yeah.



A: Not in so many words, but, you know, I mean, that's basic --



Q: Is that the only name that's popped up in  your conversations with

Arnelle, is Faye Resnick?



A: Yeah, hers is the biggest, I think,  yeah.



Q: Who else pops up?



A: I think that's the only one. Nobody else's name really pops up.



Q: Before June 12, 1994, did you know Faye Resnick?



A: Yeah.



Q: Had you ever met her?



A: Yes.



Q: Okay. How many times?



A: A handful of times.



Q: Where had you seen her?



A: Our home in Laguna. At Nicole's house.



Q: Yeah. At Bundy?



A: Nicole's house -- no, not at -- was it at Bundy? Yeah, I guess it

would have been at Bundy.



At my dad's house. And I think that's  about it.



Q: Did you ever have a conversation with  Faye about staying away from

Nicole, that she was a  bad influence on her?



A: No.



Q: Okay. Did you ever have that conversation with Nicole?



A: About staying away from Faye?



Q: Yes.



A: No, because I wasn't really aware of  their -- wasn't really aware

of what they were doing  or anything like that.



Q: You were not aware of what Nicole and Faye Resnick were doing in

the months leading up to Nicole's death. Correct?



A: No, I wasn't. I wasn't.



Q: So you never had any conversations with anybody on the subject of

whether Faye was fishy or suspicious?



A: Previous?



Q: Yes.



A: To?



Q: To Nicole's death.



A: No.



Q: And you never had a conversation with  O.J. Simpson about that

either before Nicole's death.  Right?



A: No, sir.



Q: Okay. So at no time did O.J. Simpson  tell you, you know, "I'm

really concerned about  Nicole. She's hanging out with Faye. She's

hanging out with the wrong crowd. She's leading a dangerous  life."

You had no conversations with O.J. Simpson  about that prior to

Nicole's death. True?



A: True.



Q: Okay. At any point in time from the  moment you learned of Nicole's

death to the present,  did you ever form a belief that your father

might be responsible for these deaths?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object as it's not relevant, calls for

speculation, lack of foundation.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You may answer.



A: I never formed a belief, no.



Q: Did you ever form a suspicion?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Same objections.



THE WITNESS: I formed a suspicion.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Okay. And did you ever share your suspicion with Arnelle?



A: Probably, but I don't remember.



Q: Did Arnelle ever tell you that she, too formed a suspicion that

your father might be  responsible?



A: Never.



Q: Did she ever tell that you she thought your father was guilty?



A: No, never.



Q: Did she ever tell you that she thought  your father was innocent?



A: Yeah, she has.



Q: Has she given you any explanations for  the various items of

evidence that I recounted to you?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object on the same grounds I did before:

Lack of foundation,  speculation.



THE WITNESS: Like I said before, me and her talking, that just added

more confusion to the mix.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Did she ever tell you why O.J. Simpson's blood was found at the

