A: Yeah. Four family members and the rest was friends.



Q: Did you invite Nicole?



A: No, I didn't.



Q: Did you invite Sydney and Justin?



A: Yes. I think Nicole was sick still.



Q: Did you -- you didn't invite her.



A: No, I didn't. Sorry.



Q: Okay. What family members were there?



A: Sydney, Justin. My Aunt Shirley and my  Uncle Benny surprised us.

They were coming back from a reunion, so they stopped by on the way,

and then my  dad came home and my sister. That's all the family was

there.



Q: And do you have any understanding as to why Nicole was not there?



A: It was my sister's friends and my friends. It was a bunch of kids.

It was a barbeque for a bunch of younger folks. I didn't even expect

my dad to come, to be perfectly honest.



Q: He showed up unexpectedly?



A: I think Arnelle knew he was coming. I didn't think he was gonna

come.



Q: Okay. And during the week of -- first  week of June, do you know if

your father went out of town at all?



A: No.



Q: What about the second week of June?



A: Yeah, I knew he went to Chicago, but --



Q: Before the Chicago trip, did you know where any of -- where he went

out of town?



A: I have no idea.



Q: Did you know that he went back East to Connecticut and Long Island?



A: No idea.



Q: Did he call you from the East?



A: Never.



Q: Okay. Did you speak to your father on  June 12, 1994 --



A: No.



Q: -- the day of the recital and of Nicole's murder?



A: No.



Q: Did you speak to him on June 11?



A: No.



Q: In person or telephone?



A: No, I don't think so.



Q: And not on June 12 either. Right?



A: No.



Q: What about Friday June 9, the day he arrived back from New York?



A: Uh-uh. I don't remember when the last  time was I saw him.



Q: When was the last time before Nicole's  death that you spoke to

your father?



A: I'd have to guess. It would be at the barbeque, that Memorial Day

barbeque.



Q: Was it Labor Day or Memorial Day?



A: Memorial Day.



Q: You didn't tell your father that you were  going to see him at the

recital -- or see him at  dinner, I should say, following the recital?



A: At the barbeque. I knew I wasn't going  to be going to the recital.

In the first place, I wouldn't have said that to him. So, no. I mean,

I don't remember -- I just remember seeing him at the barbeque, and

that was it. I never --



Q: Did you say, "I'll see you at Jackson's, where everyone is going to

after the recital"?



A: I hadn't known that yet until the Friday or Saturday before I --



Q: So you had no conversation with him at the barbeque about seeing

him at the recital --



A: Yes.



Q: -is that right?



A: Right. I didn't have a conversation with him at all about any of

that.



Q: None.



A: No.



Q: And did you have any conversation with him at the barbeque about

Nicole?



A: No.



Q: How he was feeling towards her, what was  going on in their life,

how she was, anything like that?



A: No.



Q: Okay. By the way, what was the  relationship like prior to Nicole's

death between O.J. Simpson and Sydney Simpson?



MR. LEONARD: I am going to object as being vague.



Go ahead if you can answer.



THE WITNESS: It was -- it wasn't -- there  didn't seem like anything

wrong to me. I didn't see a problem.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You didn't see any problems in that?



A: No, I didn't.



