Q: And what time was it?



A: I don't remember.



Q: Who was it?



A: My mom.



Q: What did she say?



A: She said, "Call your sister. It's important."



Q: Nothing else?



A: I don't think so.



Q: Did she tell you what had happened?



A: I was groggy. No, my mom didn't tell me.



Q: You called your sister?



A: I think so. No. You know what? I didn't talk to my mom. I can't

remember if I talked  to my mom, 'cause it was so early. I think I

talked  to my mom, hung up the phone. I can't remember if I  called

the house and Arnelle picked up the phone or if  Arnelle ended up

calling me back, but I did talk to Arnelle. It was the third phone

call made, and she  told me.



Q: You talked to your mother. She said, "Call Arnelle. "



A: She said, "Did Arnelle talk to you?" She said, "Jason, you need to

talk to her."



I said, "I don't know. The phone just rang." I said, "Okay, fine," and

I hung up the phone.



I can't remember then if I picked up the phone, called the house and

got Arnelle or if I just put the phone down and the phone rang again.



Q: Anyway, the next call was with Arnelle?



A: Yes.



Q: And what time was it?



A: When was it. 6:30, 7:00.



Q: What did Arnelle say?



A: She -- she said, "Jason, you need to come  to dad's house." She

said, "Jason," she said, "Nicole had -- Nicole had just died."



Q: What did you say?



A: I don't think I said anything. I was -- I said, "How?" I couldn't

figure out how. I thought  she had died of steroids or something. I

thought she was taking steroids because her body, every time I saw

her, had changed. I thought -- I don't know. I thought she had a heart

attack or something.



And Arnelle said, "No. She was killed,"  and that's it, and I hung up

the phone.



Q: Did she tell you how she was killed?



A: No.



Q: Is that the end of the conversation: "She was killed"?



A: "She was killed.". "She's been killed."



Q: Was anything said about your father?



A: I just hung up the phone. I said, "I'm coming over now. " I hung up

and got in my car immediately.



Q: No conversation about O.J. Simpson in the call with Arnelle?



A: No. I just got in my car. I left.



Q: Okay. And when you arrived, you went to  Rockingham?



A: I first went to my girlfriend's house on  the way 'cause I couldn't

drive. I couldn't breathe.  I couldn't do anything. I told you before,

I have epilepsy. I have to take my pills in the morning and  at night.

Sometimes -- you know, when I'm scared -- I didn't want to get too

overly excited, and on the way  I just had to pull over, and I was

right by her house, so I went there and I banged on her door, kinda 

collapsed there for a second, and -- no more than five minutes, and

said, "I gotta go get Arnelle." So I went to the house, Rockingham.



Q: With your girlfriend?



A: No. By myself. I just said, "I gotta leave."



Q: And what happened when you got to Rockingham?



A: Arnelle was outside with Kato. We couldn't go anywhere. They were

out on the curb. I tried to find out what was happening. I was asking

questions, and Kato couldn't answer any questions.  Arnelle couldn't

answer any questions. She couldn't say anything. And I tried to ask

the police. They wouldn't tell me anything.



Q: This was outside the property?



A: Yeah. They wouldn't -- they wouldn't let in. They wouldn't let us

do -- I couldn't find anything out. All I know is that Nicole's dead.

I didn't know where dad was. I was so far out of the picture, I felt

like --



Q: Did at this time Arnelle tell you that  they were trying to pin

this on your father?



A: No, she never said that.



Q: There wasn't any suspicion at that time  that they were trying to

--



A: He was out of town. When I found out he  was out of town, I was

like, "Well, when he's coming back?"



Q: Who did you ask that to?



A: Arnelle said, "Well" -- I said, "Well, where's dad?"



And she said, "He's out of town."



"Does he know?" you know, I think. And I asked questions about the

kids.



Q: What did Arnelle say when you said, "Does  he know?" You asked

Arnelle, "Does he know?" and what did she say?



A: I said, "What about dad, does he know?"  And she said, "Well, he's

out of town."



Q: Did Arnelle indicate to you whether or not she had spoken to your

father?



A: No, she never said that to me. I found  that out later.



Q: What did you find out later?



A: That she had talked to him on the phone.



Q: Before she saw you outside on the property?



A: Yes.



Q: How did you find that out?



A: TV.



Q: Did you ever ask Arnelle?



A: I think. Maybe -- I probably did. I don't remember exactly. I mean,

we did go over everything over and over and over again. I can't

remember, though, exactly.



Q: Who went over and over and over?



A: My sister and myself.



Q: When did you do that?



A: Later that night.



Q: On the 13th?



A: Yes.



Q: You mean the two of you were talking to each other, going over

everything that had happened during the day?



A: Trying to piece together the course of events from when she found

out to then.



Q: Where was Arnelle during the evening of June 12?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation, calls for speculation.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Did she tell you where she was?



A: I still don't know to this day. She was out. I don't know exactly

what she was doing.



Q: You don't know?



A: I don't know if it was a movie or something. I'm not going to

speculate, though. She was out.



Q: Did she tell you?



A: No. She might have told me, but I forgot, but she's always out.



Q: Okay. When did you first hear from your father?



A: The 13th. The 13th when he came home, and I -- I then came to the

house.



Q: So you saw him for the first time at the  house on Rockingham

sometime in the evening of Monday, June 13?



A: Exactly.



Q: He had not spoken to you on the telephone  yet?



A: No, I didn't -- no. No.



Q: Do you know whether he tried calling you?



A: No, I don't know.



Q: Were there any messages on your answering machine from him?



A: I don't remember.



Q: When you went home later that day and checked your messages, you

then heard the message from Arnelle that you received in the early

morning?



A: No. I think I might have gone out and  replayed it once my mom said

to call Arnelle and Arnelle said to come. I think I might have checked

it  then.



Q: Okay. No messages from your father --



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q:-- at any time on the 13th?



A: I don't believe so.



Q: Okay. When you saw your father on the  evening of the 13th, what

did you say to him and what did he say to you?



A: I think the first thing I said was, "I love you," and held him, and

we -- he was in the  living room, and we went into the kitchen, and we

just held each other.



Q: Just the two of you?



A: There were a couple people walking in and  out. I don't remember --



Q: What did he say to you?



A: He couldn't really say anything. And I started to talk about --

because I had talked to Justin, I started to talk about my

conversation with  Justin.



Q: What was your conversation with Justin?



A: I wanted to know what he knew, what his state of mind was and what

his -- how he was.



Q: When did you talk to Justin?



A: I talked to Justin from my apartment some point in the afternoon of

that day, the 13th.



Q: By telephone?



A: Yeah.



Q: They were at the Brown residence?



A: Yeah, they were in Laguna.



Q: You also spoke to Sydney?



A: I didn't speak to Sydney. I don't think  she wanted to talk on the

phone or something.



MR. LEONARD: You have to speak up.



THE WITNESS: I'm sorry. Sorry.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You said you did not speak to Syndey --



A: I don't feel like talking loud about all this.



Q: -- because why?



A: Sorry. I didn't talk to -- I'm sorry.



A: What did you just say?



Q: I said, did you also talk to Sydney?



A: No, I didn't talk to Sydney.



Q: You spoke to Justin on the telephone, and  tell us what that --

tell us what was said in that  conversation.



A: I wanted to know how he was doing, how he was, what he was doing. I

was kinda stuck because I didn't know what to say to him, but I wanted

to talk to him. You know, I mean, I found myself talking to him, but

then I was like, you know, Christ, what just happened, you know. I

didn't -- and then I was stuck. I didn't know what the hell to say to

him.



And then he just told me, "Mommy's dead," and then I just collapsed,

told him I couldn't talk to him and that I'd talk to him later and

that I loved him.



Q: You called him back -- oh, you said you would talk to him later.



A: Yeah.



Q: Did he tell you anything about what had  happened that evening?



A: No. I didn't ask him.



Q: And have you ever?



A: No.



Q: And you haven't asked Sydney. Right?



A: No.



Q: Do you know anybody who has?



A: Not to my knowledge.



Q: Do you know of anyone who has told you  what Sydney has said about

that evening?



A: No.



Q: You told your father on the evening of the 13th when you were in

the kitchen with him what transpired in your call with Justin?



A: Yeah. Yes.



Q: By this time did you have any information or knowledge that the

police viewed him as a suspect,  the evening of the 13th?



A: Yeah it was all over the news.



Q: Okay. Did you talk to him about that  circumstance?



A: No, I didn't.



Q: And did he mention anything to you?



A: Quickly, I think.



Q: What did he say?



A: I think the words were just about how bad  everything was, and then

quickly he said-and then -- I think he said, "I think I've got a big 

target on my chest," is what he said. Actually, that's exactly what he

said.



Q: What exactly did he say?



A: "I feel like I have a big target on my  chest."



Q: Meaning people were aiming at him?



A: Yeah.



Q: Is that all that he said?



A: About that, yes.



Q: How long were you there that evening?



A: I might have spent the night. I'm not quite sure. It was a weekday.



Q: And who was there that evening at the house?



A: Felt like everybody I know was there.



Q: Do you remember who was there?



A: Yeah.



Q: Who?



A: Some people. My sister Arnelle, my Uncle Benny, my Aunt Shirley, my

cousins Tony, Tracy  and Terry came, my girlfriend had come --



Q: [Name Deleted]?



A: [Name Deleted]. Cathy Randa, Gigi I believe was there -- I'm

assuming was there.



Q: Mark Slotkin?



A: Yeah, I remember he came. I can't remember if he came that day or

if he came later that  week.



Q: Skip Taft?



A: Skip, yeah, was there.



Q: Kato Kaelin?



A: Kato was there, yeah.



Q: Ron Shipp?



A: Yeah, Ron was there.



Q: Ron was a friend of yours. Right?



A: Friend of mine?



Q: Yeah.



A: No, I wouldn't call him a friend of mine.



Q: Prior to the murders.



A: No.



Q: Not a friend of yours?



A: Not mine, no.



Q: Friend of your father's?



A: I call him an acquaintance.



Q: Not a friend?



A: No. I'd fit A.C. more in the category of  friend. Ron's more like

an acquaintance.



Q: The next level down, you mean?



A: Next level down? No, I don't know. I mean, people you hang out with

kinda, and there's  people you're really like tight with.



Q: Did you ever have a falling-out with  Ron Shipp?



A: Never.



Q: Okay. Any argument with him or dispute  with him of any kind?



A: No, I never had any dispute with him.



Q: Okay. Did you ever confide in him about any problems you were

having with your father?



A: No.



Q: Okay. Did you ever take a baseball bat, by the way, and beat up a

bronze statue of your father in the yard?



A: Yeah, when I was a kid. I was hitting everything, though. The

statue was one of the things I hit. I hit a tree.



Q: Did you ever beat that in anger about  your father?



A: It wasn't about my father, no. I wanted  a party, and I was gonna

throw a party, and I got  busted. My dad found out that I was going to

have a party that night. He said I couldn't have a party.



Q: And what did you do?



A: I got mad, and I had a bat and I started hitting a tree outside,

and I think I hit a couple  other things, bushes and stuff like that,

and I hit the statue. I also hit -- there's another statue of a 

tennis player.



Q: You hit them both?



A: Yeah. And don't forget the tree.



Q: You hit the tree and the statues. Right?



A: And a couple of plants, I think.



Q: And a couple of plants.



A: Yeah, I think.



Q: Did you damage the statue of your father?



A: Slightly.



Q: Did you hit it a lot of times?



A: No. Just once.



Q: Just one shot.



A: Yeah.



Q: Is that right?



A: Yes, sir.



Q: Okay. Do you recall any conversation between Kato Kaelin and your

father on the evening of  June 13?



A: No.



Q: Okay. When you first saw your father,  did you notice if he had a

cut on his finger?



A: No. I actually looked at his hands, and  I didn't notice anything.



Q: No cuts?



A: Uh-uh.



Q: Why did you look?



A: Curiosity.



Q: To see if he was the murderer?



A: Just curiosity. I mean, just -- I couldn't believe this, and I

looked -- I was looking at his whole person.



Q: You couldn't believe that he might be the killer. Right?



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



THE WITNESS: Yeah.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You wanted to see if he had any signs of being in a struggle.

Right?



A: Or anything like that, yeah. I mean, I was -- yeah, curiosity, I

gotta say, did get me.



Q: Did you know that evening that Nicole had  been killed by a knife?



A: No, I didn't. I assumed that, though.



Q: And you saw no bruises, marks or cuts of any kind on your father.

Right?



A: No.



Q: And did you see --



MS. ROIT: Which night are we talking about?



MR.PETROCELLI: The night of June 13th when he first saw O.J. Simpson.



Q: Correct?



A: Correct.



Q: And you didn't see any bandages or Band-Aids or dressings for a

wound?



A: No, I don't remember seeing anything like that.



Q: Why did you assume that Nicole had been killed by a knife?



A: That's what's in the movies usually. I don't know. If someone says

if their throat was cut, I just assumed --



Q: You had heard her throat was cut by this time?



A: I think so.



Q: And then you assumed then it was by a knife. Right?



A: Yeah. I mean, it wasn't a spoon or a sword. I just -- I don't know.



Q: Did your father collect knives?



A: Not that I knew of.



Q: Before Nicole's death, did you have any knowledge of your father

having collected or saved or  bought knives?



A: Never. It didn't --



Q: You ever see any knives around the house  other than in the

kitchen?



A: Only knives he ever had were Swiss Army knives, and that's because

he had something to do with the company, I think.



Q: And were those knives of different sizes and shapes?



A: No. There was a -- utility pocket knives and knives that go on a

key chain.



Q: Small knives?



A: Small ones that you would like use to clean your nails.



Q: That's the only knives you've ever seen --



A: Yeah.



Q: -- him have?



A: Yeah.



Q: Other than kitchen knives.



A: Yes.



Q: What about camping knives?



A: No, I never seen --



Q: Fishing knives?



A: I've never seen any.



Q: You ever go camping or fishing with your father?



A: No.



Q: Did you ever go camping or fishing with  Nicole?



A: No.



Q: Your father collect guns?



A: As a hobby, you mean? I don't know. I don't know. I know he had

some.



Q: He had guns?



A: Yeah, but I don't know if he got more than one for a hobby or if he

literally thought he  might need it. I don't know.



Q: You're aware your father had filmed a pilot called FROGMAN?



A: Yeah.



Q: And you're aware that he had used a knife  in the FROGMAN footage?



A: I am now, yes.



Q: At the time you were not?



A: No.



Q: Were you aware that he bought a knife in  early May of 1994 at a

Los Angeles cutlery shop?



A: Now I am, yes.



Q: But not at the time?



A: No.



Q: And you never saw the knife that he bought at the cutlery shop?



A: Have I ever seen it?



Q: Prior to Nicole's death.



A: I think.



Q: Where did you see it?



A: It was in my dad's bathroom.



Q: When did you see it there?



A: When the judge came by to pick it up.



Q: You were there at the time?



A: Yeah.



Q: And you saw the judge find the knife?



A: I saw the judge, yeah.



Q: Where did he find it in your dad's bathroom?



A: There's a vanity and two mirrors this way  (Indicating) and a

mirror that way (Indicating). You know, you open the mirror and that's

where you put  medicines.



Q: Surprise you to see a knife in there?



A: Sort of, yeah.



Q: Is that the first time you had seen that  knife?



A: Yeah.



Q: Okay. Did you see any cut on your  father's hands or fingers the

rest of that week of June 13?



A: After that, no, I didn't. No.



Q: Not at all. Right?



A: No.



Q: Okay. And you saw any marks on his body  that week?



A: No.



Q: Okay. Previously on the record when I was talking about Nicole's

notes of incidents of  abuse, I had referred to Exhibit 86 and that

was  Exhibit 88 I meant to say. Exhibit 86 is the document that I

showed you that had her account of the June 3  conversation.



After the evening of June 13, when did you next see your father?



A: That would be the viewing, I think. The viewing.



Q: And between the Monday, the 13th, and the  viewing on the 15th, did

you talk to your father at  all?



A: I think I talked to him a couple times on  the phone.



Q: Okay. And do you know where he was staying?



A: At Bob Kardashian's house.



Q: And you called him there from time to  time?



A: I didn't call him. I think he called.



Q: And what did he tell you in those conversations?



A: He wanted to know how we were. We wanted to know how he was. I

wanted to see him, you know.



Q: Did you go see him?



A: No.



Q: Why not?



A: Because I was there to take care of the family. I guess he thought

it was a better idea I stayed at the house.



Q: That you stay where?



A: At the house.



Q: At whose house?



A: Rockingham. I guess. I guess.



Q: What family was at Rockingham? The aunts  and uncles?



A: My sister.



Q: And Sydney and Justin were where?



A: In Laguna.



Q: You didn't see Sydney and Justin until when?



A: I didn't see them until five days later or something like that.



Q: At the funeral?



A: Not the funeral. The wake. The wake.  That's what it's called.

Right?



Q: The viewing?



A: The viewing.



Q: So that's when you first saw Sydney and  Justin?



A: Yeah.



Q: Okay.  And that's the next time you also saw your father. Right?



A: Yeah.



Q: Did you drive down there with him?



A: We all drove down I think together, but -- no. He was there when we

got there.



Q: You got there with whom?



A: With my sister Arnelle and my cousin  Tracy and my cousin Tony and

I think my cousin  Tracy -- I mean Terry.



Q: Did your father tell you at any time in  these conversations before

the viewing that he was  contemplating killing himself?



A: No.



Q: Did he at any time make you think that he might kill himself?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Vague.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Okay. You can answer.



A: Did he ever tell me if he felt like killing himself?



Q: Yeah. Did he ever cause you to be concerned that he might kill

himself?



A: No. I didn't think about it. He didn't  seem like it to me.



Q: You didn't get that sense from him?



A: No.



Q: Okay. Did you quit your job that week,  by the way?



A: I didn't quit, no. They gave me some time off.



Q: Did you have a set of cooking knives?



A: Yeah.



Q: And did you ever take those knives off  of, you know, your work

premises?



A: All the time.



Q: And where did you keep those cooking knives?



A: In a bag, chef's bag.



Q: In where?



A: What do you mean?



Q: The bag.



A: The bag, I'll take it home with me.



