A: No.



Q: Did he tell you that he had contacted  Louis Marx?



A: No.



Q: And Wayne Hughes?



A: No.



Q: And asked these people to help them care  for you?



A: No.



Q: You knew none of that?



A: No, he never said anything like that to me.



Q: Okay. Did you learn at some point that week that he was going to be

arrested?



A: Yeah. When he was, when they were  looking for him.



Q: Were you at the Kardashian home on Friday  morning when your father

was to surrender to the  police?



A: No.



Q: Did you know that he was to surrender on  Friday morning?



A: Yeah. Yeah.



Q: When did you find that out?



A: Friday.



Q: From whom?



A: A news station.



Q: Nobody called you?



A: No. Not me. There was a lot of people  in my dad's house, so the

phone was ringing off the  hook.



Q: You were living at your dad's house that week. Right?



A: Yeah, I was staying there. I mean --



Q: And you learned on Friday morning in your  dad's house that he was

to surrender that day to the police?



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Is that what you're saying?



A: No. I found out that they went to the house. It was on the news. By

the time I found out  on the news, they had said that he's supposed to

be here and he's not.



Q: So you found out the information from the  news on the television.



A: Yeah.



Q: Not from persons in the house or in the  family.



A: No. I didn't know. I didn't even know he was going to get arrested

until the news said that  they were looking for him.



A: Okay. So your dad didn't call you on the morning of the 17th to

inform you that a decision had been made --



A: Oh, no.



Q: -- by the LAPD to arrest him.



A: No.



Q: Okay. So when you last saw your dad, let's say Thursday at the

funeral, you didn't know  whether or not he was going to be arrested

the next day. Right?



A: No, I didn't know that.



Q: Did you then see on the news what  transpired with your father

taking off with  Mr. Cowlings in the Bronco?



A: Some of it.



Q: Did you sit there and watch it the whole  time?



A: No. I mean, we were in the house. The  police came. We had to leave

the house.



Q: Where did you go?



A: We started to walk down towards my friend's house, who lives about

a block away, and -- so I wasn't watching any TV, but the street was

packed full of people and cameras and everything, and we went to my

friend Steve's house, his front yard. We were all standing outside of

his front yard.



Q: At some point in the day the police had you evacuate the house?



A: Yes.



Q: When was that?



A: That was when I guess they confirmed or  A.C. had confirmed that he

was bringing my father back  to the house.



Q: Did you talk to your father while he was in the car at all?



A: No.



Q: Did it become apparent to you from watching the news accounts that

he might kill himself?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Calls for speculation, lack of foundation.



THE WITNESS: I didn't know.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Did you know why he had fled the police?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation.



THE WITNESS: I didn't know why, no.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You had no clue as to why he had failed to surrender himself?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation.



THE WITNESS: No.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Okay. Did you know that he had a gun in  the back seat of the car

with him?



A: I found out.



Q: From watching television?



A: Yeah.



Q: Okay. You never spoke to him in that Bronco?



A: No.



Q: No calls between him and you?



A: No.



Q: Okay. You spent the rest of that day until he arrived where? On the

front lawn of your  friends?



A: No. Only partly. I think we were there  for 20 minutes.



Q: Then where did you go?



A: We all went outside because he was getting closer to home.



Q: So you left the house when he was close to home.



A: Yeah, we all went outside 'cause --



Q: I see.



A: We all went outside.



Q: And you were on the outside for 20 minutes or so; then he returned

to Rockingham, Is  that what you're saying?



A: No. The total amount of time we were at  the house might have been

about 20 minutes. We might have spent --we spent -- as soon as we got

to the house, we were standing outside, my sister, we were all in a

circle praying, and then we went inside to find out what was going on,

looked at the TV. This is all in the time of maybe 20 minutes. Right?



We were looking at the TV and my sister was still saying some more

prayers, and then as he had gotten -- he had gotten off the freeway,

and I just -- we kinda thought that maybe he was going to be coming 

up Bristol, and my friend lives right there at the  corner of Bristol

and Ashford, so we went outside.



So everybody was outside, out on the corner on the street. Sure

enough, they came rolling up the street.



Q: Who is "they"?



A: My dad and Allen.



Q: And they drove in the property?



A: They drove in the property.



Q: And where were you when this was taking  place?



A: I was right in front of the car -- on the  side of the car.



Q: Did you run to the car?



A: Yeah.



Q: For what reason?



A: Desperation.



Q: To do what? To stop your father from killing himself?



A: To stop --



MR. LEONARD: Objection.



THE WITNESS: To stop him, to talk to him.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Did you get to him?



A: I didn't physically really get to him.



Q: Why not?



A: 'Cause the car was separated. The window  was rolled up and A.C.

was between us.



Q: Okay. Did you -- did the door open?



A: No. A.C.'s big, man. I couldn't get by him.



Q: What did you do?



A: I was so -- I was so full of energy, I tried to reach through

A.C.'s window, and A.C. stopped  me and pushed me back, and I guess it

kinda shocked me  and brought me back down to reality. And those cars,

 the back window's tinted, so I never really even saw  my dad.



And I had the police behind me yelling,  and then A.C. yelling, and it

was -- I just turned  around and just said, "Jesus  just get back in

the house and let these guys handle it,"



Q: So you never did make contact with your  father?



A: No.



Q: And you went into the house to -- and he came into the house

shortly thereafter?



A: A Little bit a while after, yeah.



Q: Did you talk to him in the house?



A: No. There was like a whole police department in the house.



Q: You never got a chance to talk to him at all?



A: No. I saw him for a quick second from a  distance, from a far

distance. That was it. That was  it. I was like handcuffed in the

corner of the house.



Q: You were handcuffed?



A: Yeah.



Q: Why were you handcuffed?



A: Well, this nut-head, me, just ran out  after the car and jumped

over two police cars, and they didn't want to let me go. I think it

was pretty wise on their part.



Q: Before Nicole's murder, what was your father's relationship like

with the LAPD?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Vague. Calls for speculation, lack of

foundation.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: You can answer.



A: The whole police department?



Q: Yeah. To your knowledge it was generally positive and favorable.

Correct?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Same objections.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



A: Correct?



A: For the police officers he knew, yeah.



Q: You are not aware of any trouble that he  had with the police

department prior to June 12 of 1994. Correct?



A: I am not aware of any.



Q: In fact, you are seen in some photographs with an LAPD cap. Right?



A: Yeah. I like that cap.



Q: And you got that cap from whom?



A: I don't remember. I'm assuming it was  from Ron because Ron Shipp

was a police officer, I  think, so... I think I got it from him.



Q: So as far as you knew, your father's  dealings with the LAPD were

favorable and positive.  Right?



MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation, calls for speculation.



THE WITNESS: As far as I knew.



BY MR. PETROCELLI:



Q: Correct?



A: Correct.



Q: Are you aware of any information to the effect that the police

